= 127.9\n|Apr sun = 173.7\n|May sun = 202.1\n|Jun sun = 213.6\n|Jul sun = 233.0\n|Aug sun = 217.7\n|Sep sun = 162.3\n|Oct sun = 112.6\n|Nov sun = 68.1\n|Dec sun = 46.9\n|year sun = \n|source 1 = M\u00e9t\u00e9o Climat<ref>{{cite web\n| url = http://meteo-climat-bzh.dyndns.org/listenormale-1981-2010-7-p67.php\n| title = Climate normals for France 1981\u20132010\n| language = French\n| publisher = M\u00e9t\u00e9o Climat\n| accessdate = 16 June 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n| url = http://meteo-climat-bzh.dyndns.org/index.php?page=stati&id=90\n| title = Extreme values for Reims\n| language = French\n| publisher = M\u00e9t\u00e9o Climat\n| accessdate = 16 June 2019}}</ref>\n| date = June 2019\n}}\n\n==Administration==\nReims functions as a [[Subprefectures in France|subprefecture]] of the [[Departments of France|department]] of [[Marne (department)|Marne]],<ref name=EB1911/> in the administrative [[Regions of France|region]] of [[Grand Est]]. Although Reims is by far the largest commune in its department, [[Ch\u00e2lons-en-Champagne]] is the [[Prefectures in France|prefecture]].\n\n==Economy==\nRue de Vesle is the main commercial street (continued under other names), traversing the city from southwest to northeast through the [[Place Royale, Reims|Place Royale]].<ref name=EB1911/>\n\n==Cityscape==\n===Architecture===\n[[File:Cath\u00e9drale de Reims et Palais du Tau.jpg|thumb|[[Reims cathedral]] and [[Palace of Tau]]]]\n[[Reims Cathedral]] is an example of [[French Gothic architecture]].\n\n[[File:Basilique Saint-Remi de Reims, Southwest view 20140306 1.jpg|thumb|left|[[Basilica of Saint-Remi]]]]\nThe [[Basilica of Saint-Remi]], founded in the 11th century \"over the chapel of St. Christophe where [[Saint Remigius|St. Remi]] was buried\",<ref name=\"The National Geographic Traveler: France\">{{Cite book|title=The National Geographic Traveler: France|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AZfWAAAAMAAJ}}</ref> is \"the largest [[Romanesque architecture|Romanesque]] church in northern France, though with later additions.\"<ref name=\"The National Geographic Traveler: France\"/>\n\nThe Church of Saint-Jacques dates from the 13th to the 16th centuries. A few blocks from the cathedral, it stands {{as of | 2009 | lc = on}} in a neighbourhood of shopping and restaurants. The churches of Saint-Maurice (partly rebuilt in 1867), Saint-Andr\u00e9,<ref name=EB1911/> and Saint-Thomas (erected from 1847 to 1853, under the patronage of [[Cardinal Gousset]], now buried within its walls<ref name=EB1911/>) also draw tourists.\n\n[[File:Reims - temple (13).JPG|thumb|A stained glass window of the [[Protestant Church of Reims]]]]\nThe [[Protestant Church of Reims]], built in 1921\u20131923 over designs by [[Charles Letrosne]], is an example of [[flamboyant]] neo-Gothic architecture.\n\nThe [[H\u00f4tel de Ville, Reims|H\u00f4tel de Ville]], erected in the 17th century and enlarged in the 19th, features a [[pediment]] with an equestrian statue of [[Louis XIII of France|Louis XIII]] (reigned 1610 to 1643).<ref name=EB1911>{{EB1911|wstitle=Reims|inline=1}}</ref>\n\n{{multiple image|align=left|width=200|direction=vertical|image1=Reims, die Man\u00e8ge.JPG|image2=Reims, the Man\u00e8ge.JPG|footer=The [[Reims Man\u00e8ge and Circus]]}}\n[[Narcisse Brunette]] was the architect of the city for nearly 50 years in the 19th century. He designed the [[Reims Man\u00e8ge and Circus]], which \"combines stone and brick in a fairly sober classical composition.\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=Architecture in France, 1800\u20131900|page=92|author1=Lemoine, Bertrand|author2=Bonfante-Warren, Alexandra|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7dVPAAAAMAAJ|year=1998}}</ref>\n\nExamples of [[Art Deco]] in Reims include the [[Carnegie Library of Reims|Carnegie library]].\n\nThe [[Foujita Chapel]], built in 1965\u20131966 over designs and with frescos by Japanese\u2013French artist [[Tsuguharu Foujita]], has been listed as a ''[[monument historique]]'' since 1992.<ref name=\"gouv\">{{cite web|url=http://www.culture.gouv.fr/public/mistral/merimee_fr?ACTION=RETROUVER&FIELD_1=cmer1&VALUE_1=reims&FIELD_2=cmer4&VALUE_2=chapelle&FIELD_3=cmer5&VALUE_3=&FIELD_4=AUTR&VALUE_4=&FIELD_5=TOUT&VALUE_5=&FIELD_6=titre%20courant&VALUE_6=&FIELD_7=date%20protection&VALUE_7=&FIELD_8=DOSURLP&VALUE_8=%20&NUMBER=1&GRP=0&REQ=%28%28reims%29%20%3aLOCA%2cPLOC%2cINSEE%20%20ET%20%20%28%28chapelle%29%20%3aDENO%2cPARN%2cREMA%2cACTU%2cPDEN%2cMHPP%20%29%29&USRNAME=nobody&USRPWD=4%24%2534P&SPEC=9&SYN=1&IMLY=&MAX1=1&MAX2=100&MAX3=100&DOM=Tous |title=French Culture Ministry: listing of the Foujita chapel |publisher=culture.gouv.fr|accessdate=16 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Culture==\n===Museums===\nThe [[Palace of Tau]] contains such exhibits as statues formerly displayed by the cathedral, treasures of the cathedral from past centuries, and royal attire from coronations of French kings.\n\n[[File:Hall in Saint-Remi Museum, Reims.jpg|thumb|[[Mus\u00e9e Saint-Remi]]]]\nThe [[Mus\u00e9e Saint-Remi]], formerly the Abbey of Saint-Remi, contains tapestries from the 16th century donated by the archbishop Robert de Lenoncourt (uncle of the [[Robert de Lenoncourt (cardinal)|cardinal of the same name]]), marble capitals from the fourth century AD, furniture, jewellery, pottery, weapons and glasswork from the sixth to eighth centuries, medieval sculpture, the fa\u00e7ade of the 13th-century musicians' House, remnants from an earlier abbey building, and also exhibits of Gallo-Roman arts and crafts and a room of pottery, jewellery and weapons from Gallic civilization, as well as an exhibit of items from the Palaeolithic to the Neolithic periods. Another section of the museum features a permanent military exhibition.\n\nThe [[Museum of Fine Arts, Reims|Museum of Fine Arts]] is housed in the former Abbey of Saint-Denis. The former Coll\u00e8ge des J\u00e9suites has also become a museum.\n\n[[File:Reims - mus\u00e9e de la Reddition (01).JPG|thumb|The Museum of the Surrender]]\nThe Museum of the Surrender is the building in which on 7 May 1945, [[Dwight D. Eisenhower|General Eisenhower]] and the Allies received the unconditional surrender of the German [[Wehrmacht]].\n\n===Theaters===\n[[File:Op\u00e9ra de Reims 2015.JPG|thumb|left|[[Reims Opera House]]]]\nVenues include the [[Reims Opera House]], built in 1873 and renovated in 1931\u20131932, and the [[Reims Man\u00e8ge and Circus]], dating from 1865 and 1867.\n\nThe Com\u00e9die de Reims was inaugurated in 1966.\n\n===Libraries===\nLibraries in Reims include a [[Carnegie Library of Reims|Carnegie library]] which was built in the 1920s.\n\n===Festivals and events===\nEvery year in June, the ''F\u00eates Johanniques'' commemorate the entrance of Joan of Arc into Reims in 1429 and the coronation of Charles VII of France in the cathedral.\n\nA [[Christmas market]] is held on the parvis of Reims Cathedral (Place du Cardinal-Lu\u00e7on).\n\n===Wine and food===\n[[File:Reims Place Erlon.jpg|thumb|Place Drouet d'Erlon]]\nRestaurants and bars are concentrated around Place Drouet d'Erlon in the city centre.\n\nReims, along with [[\u00c9pernay]] and [[Ay, Marne|Ay]], functions as one of the centres of champagne production. Many of the largest [[List of champagne producers|champagne-producing houses]], known as ''les grandes marques'', have their headquarters in Reims, and most open for tasting and tours. Champagne ages in the many caves and tunnels under Reims, which form a sort of maze below the city. Carved from [[chalk]], some of these passages date back to Roman times.\n\nThe ''[[biscuit rose de Reims]]'' is a biscuit frequently associated with Champagne wine.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Riches of France: A Shopping and Touring Guide to the French Provinces|last=Clemente|first=Maribeth|publisher=St. Martin's Press}}</ref> Reims was long renown for its ''[[pain d'\u00e9pices]]'' and ''nonnette''.<ref>''[[Encyclop\u00e9die M\u00e9thodique]]: Arts et M\u00e9tiers m\u00e9caniques'', volume 5 (1788), p. 462.</ref>\n\n===Sports===\n[[File:Circuit de Reims-Gueux - 002.jpg|thumb|left|[[Reims-Gueux]] circuit]]\nBetween 1925 and 1969 Reims hosted the ''[[Grand Prix de la Marne]]'' [[auto racing|automobile race]] at the circuit of [[Reims-Gueux]]. The [[French Grand Prix]] took place here 14 times between 1938 and 1966.\n\n{{As of | 2016}} the football club ''[[Stade Reims]]'', based in the city, competed in the [[Ligue 1]], the highest tier of French football. ''Stade Reims'' became the outstanding team of France in the 1950s and early 1960s and reached the final of the [[European Cup of Champions]] twice in that era.\n\nIn October 2018, the city hosted the second [[Teqball]] World Cup.\n\nThe city has hosted the [[Reims Marathon]] since 1984.\n\n==Infrastructure==\n===Transport===\nReims is served by two main railway stations: [[Gare de Reims]] in the city centre, the hub for regional transport, and the new [[Gare de Champagne-Ardenne TGV]] {{convert|5|km|0|abbr=off}} southwest of the city with high-speed rail connections to Paris, Metz, Nancy and Strasbourg. The motorways [[A4 autoroute|A4]] (Paris-Strasbourg), [[A26 autoroute|A26]] (Calais-Langres) and [[A34 autoroute|A34]] intersect near Reims.\n\nPublic transport within the city consists of buses and a [[Reims tramway|tramway]], the latter opened in 2011.\n\nThe [[Canal de l'Aisne \u00e0 la Marne]] is a waterway.\n\n===Parks and gardens===\n[[File:Reims - Grille des Basses-Promenades (2).JPG|thumb|Paris Gate, Basses Promenades]]\nAmong the parks and gardens of Reims are the Parc de Champagne, where a [[Monument to the Heroes of the Black Army]] is located, and the Promenades.\n\n==Higher education==\nThe [[University of Reims Champagne-Ardenne|URCA]] (Universit\u00e9 de Reims Champagne-Ardenne) was founded in 1548. This multidisciplinary university develops innovative, fundamental, and applied research. It provides more than 18 000 students in Reims (22 000 in Champagne-Ardenne) with a wide initial undergraduate studies program which corresponds to society's needs in all domains of the knowledge. The university also accompanies independent or company-backed students in continuing professional development training.\nThe [[Sciences Po Paris|Institut d'Etudes politiques de Paris]], the leading French university in social and political sciences, also known as Sciences Po, opened a new campus in the {{Interlanguage link multi|Coll\u00e8ge des J\u00e9suites de Reims|fr}} in 2010. It hosts both the Europe-Africa and Europe-America Program<ref name=\"sciences-po\">{{cite web|url=http://college.sciences-po.fr/sitereims/|title=Welcome &#124; Sciences Po - College Universitaire de Reims - Campus Euro-Am\u00e9ricain|publisher=college.sciences-po.fr|accessdate=10 October 2014}}</ref> with more than 1500 students in the respective programs. In 2012 the first Reims [[Model United Nations]] was launched, which gathered 200 international students from all the Sciences Po campuses. Daniel Rondeau, the ambassador of France to [[UNESCO]] and a French writer, is the patron of the event. [[NEOMA Business School]] (former [[Reims Management School]]) is also one of the main schools in Reims.\n\n==Notable residents==\nThose born in Reims include:\n\n* [[Adolphe d'Archiac]] (1802\u20131868), geologist and [[paleontologist]]\n* [[Jean Baudrillard]] (1929\u20132007), [[culture theory|cultural theorist]] and philosopher\n* [[Nicolas Bergier]] (1567-1623), scholar of [[Roman roads]]\n* [[Roger Caillois]] (1913\u20131978), [[intellectual]]\n* [[Jean-Baptiste Colbert]] (1619\u20131683), [[Minister of the Economy, Finance and Industry (France)|French minister of finance]] from 1665 to 1683 during the reign of [[Louis XIV of France|King Louis XIV]]\n* {{Interlanguage link multi|Eug\u00e8ne Courmeaux|fr}} (1817\u20131902), librarian of Reims, fervent [[republicanism|republican]]\n* [[Jean Del Val]] (1891-1975), actor\n* [[Jean-Baptiste Drouet, Count d'Erlon]] (1765\u20131844), [[marshal of France]] and a soldier in [[Napoleon]]'s army\n* [[Paul Fort]] (1872\u20131960), poet\n* [[Nicolas Eug\u00e8ne G\u00e9ruzez]] (1799\u20131865), critic\n* [[Pauline Ferrand-Pr\u00e9vot]] (born 1992), world champion cyclist\n* [[Nicolas de Grigny]] (1672\u20131703), [[organist]] and composer\n* [[Maurice Halbwachs]] (1877\u20131945), philosopher and [[sociologist]]\n* [[Jean L\u00e9vesque de Burigny]] (1692-1785), historian\n* [[Marie-Claire Jamet]] (born 1933), classical harpist\n* [[Guillaume de Machaut]] (1300\u20131377), composer and poet (Machaut was most likely born in Reims or nearby, and spent most of his adult life there)<ref>Oxford Music Online</ref>\n* [[Henri Marteau]] (1874\u20131934), violinist and composer\n* [[Merolilan of Rheims]], Irish cleric\n* [[Olivier M\u00e9tra]] (1830\u20131889), composer, conductor\n* [[Maurice P\u00e9zard]] (1876\u20131923), archaeologist and assyriologist\n* [[Robert Pires]] (born 1973), [[Football World Cup|World Cup]] winner, footballer for [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] and for [[Villarreal CF]]\n* [[Patrick Poivre d'Arvor]] (born 1947), television journalist and writer\n* [[Jean-Baptiste de la Salle]] (1651\u20131719), Catholic saint, teacher and educational reformer\n* [[Jules de Saint-Pol]] (1810-1855), general\n* [[\u00c9mile Senart]] (1847\u20131928), indologist\n* [[Adeline Wuill\u00e8me]] (born 8 December 1975), [[Foil (fencing)|foil]] [[Fencing|fencer]]\n\n==International relations==\n{{See also|List of twin towns and sister cities in France}}\n\n===Twin towns \u2013 sister cities===\nReims is [[Twin towns and sister cities|twinned]] with:\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|- valign=\"top\"\n|\n*{{Coat of arms|Florence}}, Italy (1954)\n*{{Coat of arms|Brazzaville}}, [[Republic of the Congo]] (1961)\n* [[File:Canterbury Arms.svg|20px]] [[Canterbury]], United Kingdom (1962)<ref name=\"Archant twinning 3\">{{cite web|url=http://www.completefrance.com/language-culture/twin-towns|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130705094933/http://www.completefrance.com/language-culture/twin-towns|title=British towns twinned with French towns ''[via WaybackMachine.com]''|accessdate=20 July 2013|archivedate=5 July 2013|work=Archant Community Media Ltd}}</ref><ref>[https://archive.is/20120721071647/http://www.canterbury.gov.uk/buildpage.php?id=1133 Canterbury City Council \u2013 Twinning contacts. Retrieved on 14 October 2009]. Canterbury.gov.uk (1 March 2011). Retrieved on 25 August 2011.</ref>\n*{{Coat of arms|Salzburg}}, [[Austria]] (1964)\n*{{Coat of arms|Aachen}}, Germany (1967)<ref name=\"Calderdale\">{{cite web |url=http://www.calderdale.gov.uk/advice/tourism/towntwinning/towns/aachen.html |title=Aachen: Twin towns: Calderdale Council |last=Calderdale Council |work=calderdale.gov.uk |year=2013 |accessdate=2 January 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130928232645/http://www.calderdale.gov.uk/advice/tourism/towntwinning/towns/aachen.html |archivedate=28 September 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"en-db\">{{cite web |url= http://en.db-city.com/Germany--North-Rhine-Westphalia--Aachen--Aachen |title=Aachen, Aachen, North Rhine-Westphalia, Germany \u2013 City, Town and Village of the world |first= |last=en-db |work=en.db-city.com |year=2013|accessdate=3 January 2013}}</ref>\n* [[File:Seal of Virginia.svg|20px]] [[Arlington County, Virginia]], United States (2005)\n* [[File:COA Kutna Hora.png|20px]] [[Kutn\u00e1 Hora]], [[Czech Republic]] (2008)\n* [[File:Emblem of Nagoya, Aichi.svg|20px]] [[Nagoya]], [[Japan]] (2017)\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Archbishop of Reims]]\n* [[Battle of Reims (disambiguation)|Battle of Reims]]\n* [[Biscuit rose de Reims]]\n* [[Champagne (province)]]\n* Champagne\n* [[Champagne (wine region)]]\n* [[Champagne Riots]]\n* [[French wine]]\n* [[Reims Aviation]] (aircraft-maker)\n\n==Notes==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{See also|Timeline of Reims#Bibliography|l1=Bibliography of the history of Reims}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons and category}}\n{{Wikivoyage}}\n* [http://www.reims.fr/ Official website] {{in lang|fr}}\n* [http://www.reims-tourisme.com/ Tourist office website] \u2013 Official site for L'Office de Tourisme de Reims, {{in lang|en|fr}}\n* [http://college.sciences-po.fr/sitereims/ Sciences Po Paris \u2013 Euro-American campus of Reims]\n* [https://archive.is/20130102093140/http://dl.dropbox.com/u/49375129/MNUSP/ReimsMUN/Welcome.html Reims Model United Nations]\n* [http://www.maidofheaven.com/joanofarc_long_biography.asp#reims Joan of Arc and The Coronation Of Charles VII in Reims]\n* [http://archive.joan-of-arc.org/joanofarc_letter_aug_5_1429.html Joan of Arc's first letter to Reims]  \u2014 translation by Allen Williamson of the letter dictated by Joan of Arc to the city of Reims on 5 August 1429.\n* [http://archive.joan-of-arc.org/joanofarc_letter_march_16_1430.html Joan of Arc's second letter to Reims] \u2014  letter dictated by Joan of Arc to the city of Reims on 16 March 1430, translated by Allen Williamson.\n\n{{Cities in France}}\n{{Marne communes}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Reims|*]]\n[[Category:Communes of Marne (department)]]\n[[Category:Subprefectures in France]]\n[[Category:Remi]]\n[[Category:Champagne]]\n[[Category:Joan of Arc]]\n", "name_user": "Markussep", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Reims"}
{"title_page": "El Cuatrero", "text_new": "{{Infobox professional wrestler\n| name = El Cuatrero\n| image =El Cuatrero.jpg\n| image_size =\n| alt =\n| caption =El Cuatrero holding the [[CMLL World Middleweight Championship]] in the air, November 2018\n| birth_name = \n| birth_date = 1996\n| birth_place = Lagos de Moreno, Jalisco, Mexico<ref name=MedioIntro/>\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| resides =\n| spouse =\n| children =\n| family = {{Unbulleted list|[[Cien Caras]] (father)<ref name=MedioIntro/>|[[Sans\u00f3n (wrestler)|Sans\u00f3n]] (brother)<ref name=MedioIntro/>|[[M\u00e1scara A\u00f1o 2000]] (uncle)<ref name=MedioIntro/>|[[Universo 2000]] (uncle)<ref name=MedioIntro/>|[[Forastero]] (cousin)|[[Universo 2000 Jr.]] (cousin)|[[M\u00e1scara A\u00f1o 2000 Jr.]] (cousin)}}\n| alma_mater =\n| names ={{Unbulleted list|'''El Cuatrero'''|M\u00e1scara Universal}}\n| height = {{Convert|185|cm|ftin|abbr=on}}<ref name=DivinasLuchas/><!-- In Mexico they measure height in meters so that should be first -->\n| weight ={{convert|94|kg|lb|abbr=on}}<ref name=DivinasLuchas/><!--In Mexico they measure weight in kilograms so that should be first -->\n| billed =\n| trainer ={{Unbulleted list|[[Universo 2000]]<ref name=Starmedia/>|[[\u00daltimo Guerrero]]|[[Virus (wrestler)|Virus]]|[[Franco Colombo]]}}\n| debut =2010<ref name=MedioIntro/>\n| retired =\n| website =\n}}\n'''''El Cuatrero''''' (born 1996) is a Mexican ''[[Lucha libre|luchador]] enmascarado'', or [[wrestling mask|masked]] [[professional wrestler]] currently working for ''[[Consejo Mundial de Lucha Libre]]'' (CMLL) based in Mexico City. He is the son of ''lucha libre'' legend [[Cien Caras]] and the nephew of [[M\u00e1scara A\u00f1o 2000]] and [[Universo 2000]]. Cuatrero, his brother [[Sans\u00f3n (wrestler)|Sans\u00f3n]] and their cousin [[Forastero]] form a trio known as ''Nueva Generaci\u00f3n Dinamitas'' (\"New Generation Dynamites\"), the successor to ''[[Los Capos|Los Hermanos Dinamita]]'' (Cien Caras, M\u00e1scara A\u00f1o 2000 and Universo 2000). His real name is not a matter of public record, as is often the case with masked wrestlers in Mexico where their private lives are kept a secret from the wrestling fans.<ref name=Mondo>{{cite book | author= Madigan, Dan | title= Mondo Lucha Libre: the bizarre & honorable world of wild Mexican wrestling | publisher= HarperColins Publisher | year= 2007 | chapter = Okay... what is Lucha Libre? | pages = 29\u201340|isbn=978-0-06-085583-3}}</ref> His [[ring name]] is Spanish for \"The Horse thief\" or  \"The [[Cattle Rustler]]\", reflected in the cowboy-inspired ring gear and mask he wears during shows.\n\nEl Cuatrero is the current [[CMLL World Middleweight Champion]] and at one point held four championships simultaneously, which included the [[CMLL Arena Coliseo Tag Team Championship]] (with Sans\u00f3n), the [[Mexican National Trios Championship]] (with Sans\u00f3n and Forastero) and the Occidente Trios Championship (with Sans\u00f3n and Forastero). He won the mask of [[\u00c1ngel de Oro]] in the main event of CMLL's 2018 ''[[Homenaje a Dos Leyendas]]'' show on March&nbsp;16, 2018.\n\n==Personal life==\nEl Cuatrero was born in 1996, a son of [[professional wrestler]] Carmelo Reyes Gonz\u00e1lez, better known under the [[ring name]] [[Cien Caras]] (\"100 Faces\"). His older brother, known under the name [[Sans\u00f3n (wrestler)|Sans\u00f3n]] (\"[[Samson]]\") was born in 1994. His uncles Jes\u00fas (known as [[M\u00e1scara A\u00f1o 2000]]) and Andr\u00e9s ([[Universo 2000]]) were also professional wrestlers.<ref name=MondoFamily/> Several of their sons followed their fathers into professional wrestling, including [[Forastero]], [[Universo 2000 Jr.]] and [[M\u00e1scara A\u00f1o 2000 Jr.]]<ref>{{cite web | url= http://www.mediotiempo.com/mas-deportes/lucha-libre/noticias/2012/08/05/wagner-destapo-a-mascara-2000-jr | title= Wagner destap\u00f3 a M\u00e1scara 2000 Jr. | last=Rodr\u00edguez | first=Alejandro | date=August 5, 2012 | accessdate=February 19, 2013 | work=MedioTiempo | language=Spanish | trans-title=Wagner unmasks M\u00e1scara 2000 Jr.}}</ref> Initially, Carmelo Reyes did not want his sons to become professional wrestlers, wanting them to get an education instead. He reluctantly agreed that they could train for ''Lucha Libre'' with their uncle Andr\u00e9s, but only as a hobby. During their training, Carmelo noticed how serious they took it and reluctantly agreed with their choice to become professional wrestlers.<ref name=DivinasLuchas>{{cite web | url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Uz7nTR_jZSE | title=Divinas de la lucha Cuatrero y Sans\u00f3n | date=March 5, 2017 | accessdate=February 16, 2017 | first=Elisa | last=Tud\u00f3n | work=Divinas de la Luchas | language=Spanish | trans-title=Divine fighters Cuatrero and Sanson}}</ref>\n\nThere is a long tradition of wrestlers paying for the right to use a ring name in Mexican wrestling, including being allowed to portray a second or third-generation wrestler without being related to the originator.<ref name=MondoFamily>{{cite book|author=Madigan, Dan|title=Mondo Lucha a Go Go: the bizarre & honorable world of wild Mexican wrestling|publisher=[[HarperCollins]] Publisher|year=2007|chapter=A family affair|pages = 128\u2013132|isbn=978-0-06-085583-3}}</ref> It has been confirmed that wrestlers [[Cien Caras Jr.]] and [[El Hijo de Cien Caras]] are unrelated to the Reyes family, while it is unclear if [[Hijo de M\u00e1scara A\u00f1o 2000]] is a blood relative or a purely fictional relative.<ref name=Adios>{{cite web|url=http://www.record.com.mx/blog/el-hijo-del-santo/2010-12-02/el-adios-del-hijo-de-cien-caras |title=El adi\u00f3s del Hijo de Cien Caras |authorlink=El Hijo del Santo | first=El | last=Hijo del Santo |date=December 2, 2010 |accessdate=February 19, 2013 |publisher=R\u00e9cord.com |language=Spanish |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101204113931/http://www.record.com.mx/blog/el-hijo-del-santo/2010-12-02/el-adios-del-hijo-de-cien-caras |archivedate=December 4, 2010 |trans-title=Goodbye to El Hijo de Cien Caras}}</ref> Reyes later stated that he allowed the \"Cien Caras\" name to be rented by other wrestlers as his sons were very young and might not want to become professional wrestlers.<ref name=MedioIntro/>\n\n==Professional wrestling career==\n[[File:Nueva Generacion Dinamitas.jpg|thumb|left|[[Sans\u00f3n (wrestler)|Sans\u00f3n]], El Cuatrero and [[Forastero]] outside the ring in November 2018]]\nWhile the El Cuatrero name was first used in 2014, Sans\u00f3n said they made their in-ring debut around the year 2010 and worked locally in Lagos de Moreno, while finishing school.<ref name=MedioIntro>{{cite web | url=http://www.mediotiempo.com/mas-deportes/lucha-libre/noticias/2015/12/01/herederos-de-cien-caras-cerca-de-debut-en-arena-mexico | title=Herederos de Cien Caras cerca de debut en Arena M\u00e9xico | date=December 1, 2015 | accessdate=February 16, 2018 | language=Spanish | work=MedioTiempo | first=Apolo | last=Vald\u00e9s | trans-title=The successors to Cien Casas make their debut in Arena Mexico}}</ref> In an interview Cuatrero said that he wrestled briefly as \"M\u00e1scara Universal\", but his father did not like the name and suggested the name \"El Cuatrero\", Spanish for \"The [[Cattle rustler]] instead. This was inspired by the cowboy gimmick that his father and his uncles had used.<ref name=Starmedia>{{cite web | url=http://www.starmedia.com/noticias/sanson-cuatrero-reviviran-memoria-cien-caras-en-arena-mexico/ | title=Sans\u00f3n Y Cuatrero Revivir\u00e1n Memoria De Cien Caras En La Arena M\u00e9xico | date=December 28, 2015 | accessdate=February 16, 2018 | work=[[Starmedia|StarMedia]] | language=Spanish | trans-title=Sanson and Cuatrero revieve the memory of Cien Caras in Arena Mexico | archivedate=July 31, 2018  | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180731125041/https://www.starmedia.com/noticias/sanson-cuatrero-reviviran-memoria-cien-caras-en-arena-mexico}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.elsoldemexico.com.mx/deportes/Sans\u00f3n-y-Cuatrero-los-\u201cNuevos-Dinamita\u201d-198235.html | title=Sans\u00f3n y Cuatrero, los \"Nuevos Dinamita\" | date=October 23, 2015 | accessdate=February 16, 2018 | language=Spanish | work=El Sol del Mexico | first=Armando | last=Isa\u00eds | trans-title=Sanson and Cuatrero, the \"New Dynamites\"}}</ref> During their time working locally in Lagos de Moreno, the duo won their first ''[[Lucha de Apuestas]]'', or bet match, when they defeated Los Centellas (I and II) and unmasked the duo.<ref name=DivinasLuchas/>\n\n===Consejo Mundial de Lucha Libre (2014\u2013present)===\nThe Reyes  brothers worked locally until early 2014, when they began working in Guadalajara for the local ''[[Consejo Mundial de Lucha Libre]]'' (CMLL) promoters in Arena Coliseo. They trained at the CMLL wrestling school under [[\u00daltimo Guerrero]], [[Virus (wrestler)|Virus]] and [[Franco Colombo]].<ref name=Starmedia/> The Reyes brothers made their CMLL debut on March&nbsp;25, 2014, where they, along with Universo 2000, lost to the trio of [[Blue Panther]], [[Sagrado (wrestler)|Sagrado]], and [[Valiente (wrestler)|Valiente]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.cagematch.net//?id=1&nr=108892 | title=CMLL Guadalajara Martes | date=March 25, 2014 | accessdate=February 18, 2018 | work=CageMatch| language=German}}</ref> While working in Guadalajara, El Cuatrero and Sans\u00f3n competed in a tournament to determine the number one contenders for the local Occidente Tag Team Championship, but they were eliminated by the team of Flash and Flash II.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.cagematch.net//?id=1&nr=124225 | title=CMLL Guadalajara Viernes | date=January 30, 2015 | accessdate=July 29, 2018 | work=CageMatch| language=German}}</ref> The brothers teamed up with Jocker. The winners would be crowned the new Occidente Trios Champions. The team made it to the final match of the tournament but were defeated by Furia Roja, Mr. Trueno, and Ray Trueno.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.cagematch.net//?id=1&nr=128976 | title=CMLL Guadalajara Domingos | date=March 5, 2015 | accessdate=July 29, 2018 | work=CageMatch| language=German}}</ref> On November&nbsp;11, 2015, Cuatrero and Sans\u00f3n teamed up with their cousin Forastero and won the Occidente Trios Championship.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.cagematch.net//?id=1&nr=140036 | title=LLE | date=November 11, 2015 | accessdate=July 29, 2018 | work=CageMatch| language=German}}</ref>\n\nOn January&nbsp;5, 2017, El Cuatrero worked his first CMLL match in Mexico City in the company's main venue. He participated in the 2017 version of ''[[La Copa Junior]]'' but was eliminated from the tournament before the finals.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.mediotiempo.com/mas-deportes/lucha-libre/noticias/2016/01/06/puma-finalista-de-la-copa-jr-del-cmll | title=Puma, finalista de la Copa Jr. del CMLL | date=January 6, 2015 | accessdate=January 10, 2016 | work=MedioTiempo | language=Spanish | trans-title=Puma finalist in the CMLL La Copa Jr.}}</ref> At that point, the Reyes brothers began being referred to as ''Nueva Generacion Dinamitas'' (Spanish for \"New Generation Dynamites\"; NGD)\u2014a reference to their heritage. On March&nbsp;18, 2016, ''Nueva Generacion Dinamitas'' worked their first major show for CMLL, defeating [[Soberano Jr.]] and [[Oro Jr.]] in the opening match of that year's ''[[Homenaje a Dos Leyendas (2016)|Homenaje A Dos Leyendas]]'' show.<ref name=DosLeyendas2016SL>{{cite web | url=http://superluchas.com/cmll-homenaje-a-dos-leyendas-cobertura-y-resultados-21032016/ | title=CMLL \"Homenaje a Dos Leyendas\" \u2013 Cobertura y Resultados \u2013 21/03/2016 \u2013 M\u00e1ximo Sexy y Negro Casas, pelones | author=Dark Angelita | date=March 18, 2016 | accessdate=March 19, 2016 | work=[[S\u00faper Luchas]] | language=Spanish | trans-title= CMLL \"Homage to Two Legends \u2013 Coverage and results \u2013 21/02/1016 \u2013 M\u00e1ximo Sexy and Negro Casas bald}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://es-us.deportes.yahoo.com/fotos/homenaje-a-dos-leyendas-lucha-libre-arena-m%C3%A9xico-viernes-18-de-marzo-de-2016-slideshow/ | title=Homenaje a Dos Leyendas, Lucha Libre Arena M\u00e9xico, Viernes 18 de Marzo de 2016 | date=March 19, 2016 | accessdate=March 19, 2016 | publisher=[[Yahoo!]] | work=Yahoo! Deportes | first=Gonzalo | last= L\u00f3pez Peralta}}</ref> CMLL decided to have both El Cuatrero and Sans\u00f3n participate in their annual ''[[Torneo Gran Alternativa (2016)|Torneo Gran Alternativa]]'' (\"Great Alternativa Tournament\") where younger wrestlers team up with established veteran wrestlers. El Cuatrero was paired with [[Rey Bucanero]], but the duo lost to [[Trit\u00f3n (wrestler)|Trit\u00f3n]] and [[M\u00edstico II|M\u00edstico]] in the first round.<ref name=Medio2016BlockA>{{cite web | url=http://www.mediotiempo.com/mas-deportes/lucha-libre/noticias/2016/03/23/rey-escorpion-y-fujin-por-la-gran-alternativa | title=Rey Escorpi\u00f3n y Fuj\u00edn, por la Gran Alternativa | date=March 23, 2016 | accessdate=March 23, 2016 | work=MedioTiempo | language=Spanish | trans-title=Rey Escorpi\u00f3n and Fuj\u00edn go for the Gran Alternativa}}</ref> A year later, El Cuatrero was teamed up with his uncle M\u00e1scara A\u00f1o 2000 for the 2017 version of the ''[[Torneo Gran Alternativa (2017)|Torneo Gran Alternativa]]'',  but like the 2016 tournament, El Cuatrero did not make it past the first round as the team lost to [[Esfinge]] and [[Atlantis (wrestler)|Atlantis]].<ref name=2017BlockAF4W>{{cite web | url=http://www.f4wonline.com/mexico/cmll-arena-mexico-results-la-gran-alternativa-tournament-begins-236681| title=CMLL Arena Mexico Results: La Gran Alternativa tournament begins | date=June 4, 2017 | accessdate=June 11, 2017 | work=Wrestling Observer Figure Four Online | first=Chris | last=Aiken}}</ref> While El Cuatrero's first years on the main roster had seen little success, July 2017 proved a turning point in how ''Nueva Generacion Dinamitas'' was booked. El Cuatrero and Sans\u00f3n defeated [[Black Terry]] and [[Negro Navarro]] to win the [[CMLL Arena Coliseo Tag Team Championship]], CMLL's second-highest ranked tag team championship.<ref name=NGD/> Three days later the trio defeated ''[[Los Hijos del Infierno]]'' ([[Ephesto]], [[Luciferno]], and [[Mephisto (wrestler)|Mephisto]]) to win the [[Mexican National Trios Championship]], making Ephesto a triple championship.<ref name=NGDTrios/> The trio would win CMLL's ''La Copa Dinastia'', defeating the trios of Blue Panther, [[Blue Panther Jr.]], [[The Panther (wrestler)|The Panter]] and then [[Dragon Lee (wrestler)|Dragon Lee]], M\u00edstico, and [[Comandante Pierroth|Pierroth]].<ref name=CopaDinastia2017/> \n\nOn January&nbsp;19, 2018, as part of the annual [[Fantastica Mania 2018|2018 Fantastica Mania]] tour of Japan, El Cuatrero defeated [[\u00c1ngel de Oro]] to win the [[CMLL World Middleweight Championship]].<ref name=CuatreroMiddle/> The match and championship change was the beginning of a long-running storyline feud between El Cuatrero and \u00c1ngel de Oro, where challenges for a ''Lucha de Apuestas'' match soon followed.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.mediotiempo.com/lucha-libre/2018/02/07/angel-de-oro-y-cuatrero-se-jugaran-las-mascaras-en-homenaje-a-dos-leyendas | language=Spanish | accessdate=July 30, 2018 | date=February 7, 2019 | work=MedioTiempo | title=\u00c1ngel de Oro y Cuatrero se jugaran las mascaras en Homenaje a Dos Leyendas | trans-title=\u00c1ngel de Oro, fighting for the asks at Homage to Two Legends}}</ref> On February&nbsp;14, 2018, ''Nueva Generacion Dinamitas'' announced they were giving up the CMLL Arena Coliseo Tag Team Championship. Their storyline was that they were focusing on winning the [[CMLL World Tag Team Championship]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://twitter.com/CMLL_OFICIAL/status/964177915343724550 | title=Sans\u00f3n y Cuatrero renuncian al Campeonato de Parejas de la Arena Coliseo. | trans-title=Sans\u00f3n and Cuatrero give up the Arena Colise Tag Team Championship |date=February 15, 2018 | accessdate=March 11, 2018 | author=CMLL | publisher=[[Twitter]] | language=Spanish}}</ref> The storyline feud between El Cuatrero and \u00c1ngel de Oro reached its peak at the 2018 ''[[Homenaje a Dos Leyendas (2018)|Homenaje a Dos Leyendas]]'' show, where both competitors put their mask on the line in the main event match of the night. El Cuatrero defeated \u00c1ngel de Oro two falls to one, forcing him to remove his mask as per ''lucha libre'' tradition.<ref name=AngelApuesta/> El Cuatrero would later make his first and second successful defense of the CMLL World Middleweight Championship against \u00c1ngel de Oro.<ref name=CMLLMiddle>{{cite web | url=https://www.cagematch.net//?id=5&nr=93&page=5&reign=19 | title= CMLL World Middleweight Championship >> Title Reigns >> 19.01.2018 - Today: El Cuatrero| accessdate=March 4, 2020 | work=CageMatch}}</ref> At the [[CMLL 85th Anniversary Show]], the Dinamitas defeated Atlantis, El Soberano Jr., and Mistico as part of CMLL's most important show of the year.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.f4wonline.com/mexico/cmll-85th-aniversario-live-results-hair-vs-hair-tag-team-main-event-265781 | title=CMLL 85. Aniversario live results: hair vs. hair tag team main event | work=[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter|Wrestling Observer Figure Four Online]] | date=September 14, 2018 | accessdate=September 15, 2018 | first=Chris | last=Aiken}}</ref> On November&nbsp;6, 2018, Cuatrero made his third successful middleweight championship defense as he defeated [[Tit\u00e1n (wrestler)|Tit\u00e1n]].<ref name=CMLLMiddle/>\n\n2019 was the first year that the three members of Nueva Generaci\u00f3n Dinamitas participated in the annual [[Fantastica Mania 2019|Fantastica Mania]] tour of Japan, capping off the tour with a successful championship defense against \u00c1ngel de Oro, Atlantis, and Tit\u00e1n on its last day.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.f4wonline.com/japan/njpwcmll-fantastica-mania-results-my-dad-heel-wrestler-match-275026 | title=NJPW/CMLL Fantastica Mania results: 'My Dad is a heel wrestler' match | date=January 21, 2019 | accessdate=January 21, 2019 | work=[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]] | first=Ethan | last=Renner}}</ref> 2019 also marked the first year that El Cuatrero participated in the [[CMLL Universal Championship (2019)|Universal Championship]], a tournament where all 16 participants held a championship recognized by CMLL. In the opening round. he defeated perennial rival Soberano Jr. before losing to \u00daltimo Guerrero in the quarterfinals.<ref name=BlockBOvaciones>{{cite web | url=https://ovaciones.com/vence-al-maestro/ | title=\u00a1Vence al maestro! | trans-title=defeating the master | date=February 9, 2019 | accessdate=February 9, 2019 | first=Arturo | last=Rosas Platas | language=Spanish | work=Ovaciones}}</ref><ref name=BlockBMarca>{{cite web | url=https://www.marca.com/claro-mx/otros-deportes/lucha-libre/2019/02/09/5c5e6f62268e3e8f7c8b45a1.html | work=Marca Claro | title=Niebla Roja se impone en la segunda fase del torneo Campe\u00f3n Universal 2019 | trans-title=Niebla Roja looks imposing in the second phase of the 2019 Universal Championship | date=February 9, 2019 | accessdate=February 9, 2019 | language=Spanish}}</ref> For the 2019 ''[[CMLL Torneo Nacional de Parejas Incre\u00edbles (2019)|Torneo Nacional de Parejas Incre\u00edbles]]'' (\"National Incredible Teams Tournament), Cuatrero was paired up with M\u00edstico, as a ''[[Heel (professional wrestling)|rudo]]'' (The \"bad guy\") and a ''[[Face (professional wrestling)|tecnico]]'' (the \"Good guy\") team up for the event. The odd couple defeated [[Hechicero]] and [[Stuka Jr.]], then Atlantis and Negro Casas, before ultimately losing to \u00daltimo Guerrero and Volador Jr. in the semifinals.<ref name=Increibles2019B>{{cite web | url= https://www.20minutos.com.mx/deportes/noticia/ultimo-guerrero-y-volador-jr-van-a-final-de-torneo-increible-505260/0/ | title= \u00daltimo Guerrero y Volador Jr. van a final de \"Torneo incre\u00edble\"|trans-title=\u00daltimo Guerrero and Volador Jr. goes to the finals of the \u201cIncredible Tournament\u201d| language=Spanish | work=[[20 Minutos]] | author=Notimex | date=April 20, 2019 | accessdate=May 17, 2019}}</ref><ref name=Ovaciones2019B>{{cite web | url=https://ovaciones.com/volador-y-guerrero-a-la-final/ | title=Volador y Guerrero a la final | trans-title=Volador and Guerrero in the finals | language=Spanish | accessdate=May 17, 2019 | date=April 20, 2019  | work=Ovacones | first=Arturo | last=Rosas Plata}}</ref> As part of the 66th&nbsp;anniversary of Arena Puebla, NGD successfully defended the Mexican National Trios Championship against ''[[Los Ingobernables]]'' ([[El Terrible]], [[La Bestia del Ring]], and [[Rush (wrestler)|Rush]]), in what was their tenth overall championship defense.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.cagematch.net//?id=5&nr=532&page=5&reign=41 | title=Mexican National Trios Championship >> 25.07.2017 - today: La Sangre Dinamita (El Cuatrero, Forasteo & Sanson) | work=CageMatch | accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref> In December, El Cuatrero made his fourth successful defense of the CMLL World Middleweight Championship as he defeated [[Car\u00edstico]] on December&nbsp;12.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.cagematch.net//?id=1&nr=250178 | title=CMLL Sabados De Coliseo | date=December 12, 2019 | accessdate=March 31, 2020 | work=CageMatch}}</ref>\n\nThe 2020 ''[[Sin Piedad (2020)|Sin Piedad]]'' show offered Cuatrero the opportunity to become a quadruple champion as he and Sans\u00f3n challenged M\u00edstico and Car\u00edstico for the CMLL World Tag Team Championship but lost the match.<ref name=SP2020Medio>{{cite web | url=https://www.mediotiempo.com/lucha-libre/cmll/espiritu-negro-fue-desenmascarado-por-principe-diamante | title=Cay\u00f3 la primera m\u00e1scara en el 2020 dentro del CMLL; Esp\u00edritu Negro revel\u00f3 su rostro | trans-title=The first mask loss in CMLL of 2020; Espiritu Negro revealed his face | language=Spanish | date=January 2, 2020 | accessdate=January 2, 2020 | work=MedioTiempo}}</ref> During the 2020 [[Fantastica Mania 2020|Fantastica Mania]] tour, Cuatrero and his brother participated in the [[List of CMLL tag team tournaments#2020 Family tag team tournament|family tag team tournament]], where they ended up defeating ''Los Hermanos Chavez'' (\u00c1ngel de Oro and Niebla Roja) in the finals.<ref name=FM20Jan19>{{cite web | url=https://www.njpw.co.jp/tornament/220096?showResult=1 | title=NJPW presents CMLL Fantastica Mania 2020 | language=Japanese | date=January 17, 2020 | accessdate=January 17, 2020 | work=[[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]]}}</ref> On the final day of the tour, January&nbsp;20, NGD successfully defended the Mexican National Trios Championship against ''Los Hermanos Chavez'' and Tit\u00e1n.<ref name=NJPWFM202Jan20>{{cite web | url=https://www.njpw.co.jp/tornament/220098?showResult=1 | title=NJPW presents CMLL Fantastica Mania 2020 | date=January 20, 2020 | accessdate=January 20, 2020 | work=[[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]] | language=Japanese}}</ref> On February&nbsp;24, 2020, El Cuatrero and Sans\u00f3n won the ''[[#Torneo de parejas familiares|Torneo de parejas familiares]]'' (\"Family Team Tournament\") as they defeated the uncle/nephew team of Rey Bucanero and [[Drone (wrestler)|Drone]] in the first round, the father/son team of [[Euforia (wrestler)|Euforia]] and Soberano Jr. in the second round, and finally the [[Gran Guerrero]]/\u00daltimo Guerrero brothers in the finals.<ref name=NGDFamiliares/><ref name=LuchaCentral/>\n\n===Independent circuit (2014\u2013current)===\nWhile working for CMLL, Cuatrero, like all CMLL workers, is allowed to take independent circuit bookings on days he is not needed by CMLL not arranged through CMLL. On February&nbsp;19, 2017, Cuatrero and Sans\u00f3n unsuccessfully challenged Black Terry and Negro Navarro for the CMLL Arena Coliseo Tag Team Championship on a ''Lucha Memes'' show in Puebla.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.cagematch.net//?id=1&nr=173059 | title=Lucha Memes | date=February 19, 2017 | accessdate=February 4, 2020 | work=CageMatch}}</ref> NGD also successfully defended the Mexican National Tag Team Championship against Los Kamikazes del Aire (Alas de Acero, [[Aramis]], and Iron Kid) at a subsequent ''Lucha Memes'' show.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.cagematch.net//?id=1&nr=192320 | title=Lucha Memes Chairo 12 | date=May 2, 2018| accessdate=February 4, 2020 | work=CageMatch}}</ref> \n\nAs part of CMLL's collaboration with [[The Crash Lucha Libre]], Nueva Generaci\u00f3n Dinamitas has performed on several The Crash shows over the years. In their initial appearance for The Crash, Nueva Generaci\u00f3n Dinamitas lost to [[La Rebeli\u00f3n Amarilla]] ([[Bestia 666]], [[Jacob Fatu]] and [[Mecha Wolf 450]]).<ref>{{cite web | url=https://tjsports.com.mx/se-termina-la-rebelion/ |title=\u00a1Se Termina \u2018La Rebeli\u00f3n\u2019! | trans-title=The end of \"The Rebellion\" | date=September 8, 2018 | accessdate=March 3, 2020 | language=Spanish | work=TJ Sports}}</ref> The team returned to The Crash for their [[The Crash VII Aniversario|VII Anniversary Show]] show, where they lost to ''Los Lucha Bros'' ([[Pentag\u00f3n Jr.|Penta El 0M]] and [[F\u00e9nix (wrestler)|The King]]) in a match for [[The Crash Tag Team Championship]] that also included [[Reno Scum]] (Adam Thornstowe and Luster the Legend).<ref name=LuchaCentral>{{cite web | url=https://www.luchacentral.com/resultados-aniversario-vii-the-crash-espanol/ | title=\u00a1Resultados Aniversario VII The Crash ! Espanol | trans-title=Results of the Crash VII Anniversary! Spanish | date=November 3, 2018 | accessdate=November 4, 2018 | first=Miguel | last=Pe\u00f1a | work=Lucha Central | language=Spanish}}</ref><ref name=LuchaWorld>{{cite web | url=http://www.luchaworld.com/?p=86983 | title=Lucha Report for 11/4/18 | date=November 4, 2018 | accessdate=November 4, 2018 | first=Alfredo | last=Esparza | work=Lucha World}}</ref> They returned to The Crash in December 2018, losing to Bestia 666 and [[Garza Jr.]] in the main event.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://tjsports.com.mx/garza-jr-y-bestia-666-demostraron-porque-son-la-cara-de-the-crash-lucha-libre/| title=Garza Jr. Y Bestia 666 Demostraron Porque Son La Cara De The Crash Lucha Libre | trans-title=Garza Jr. Y Bestia 666 demonstrate why they are the face of The Crash Lucha Libre | work=TJ Sports | language=Spanish | accessdate=March 4, 2020 | date=December 1, 2018}}</ref> In 2019, Cuatrero and Sans\u00f3n worked an extended storyline against ''[[Los Traumas]]'' ([[Trauma&nbsp;I]] and [[Trauma&nbsp;II]]) in The Crash. In June Sans\u00f3n was forced to team up with Trauma&nbsp;I to face Cuatrero and Trauma&nbsp;I in a ''[[relevos incre\u00edbles]]'' (\"incredible pairs\" match), where the regular partners refused to wrestle against each other. In the end, Sans\u00f3n and Trauma&nbsp;I won after Trauma&nbsp;II hit El Cuatrero during the match.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.cagematch.net//?id=1&nr=231526 | title=The Crash | date=June 15, 2019 | accessdate=March 4, 2020 | work=CageMatch}}</ref> This was followed by a tag team match where NGD defeated Los Traumas by disqualification as part of their ongoing storyline.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.cagematch.net//?id=1&nr=233101 | title=FCP Project Mexico| date=September 7, 2019 | accessdate=March 4, 2020 | work=CageMatch}}</ref>\n\nOn June&nbsp;16, 2019, Cuatrero, Forastero, and Sans\u00f3n appeared at the International Wrestling Revolution Group's annual [[Festival de las M\u00e1scaras (2019)|Festival de las M\u00e1scaras]] show. The trio defeated their cousin M\u00e1scara A\u00f1o 2000&nbsp;Jr., teaming with Capo del Sur and Capo del Norte, who both use ring characters inspired by the original ''Los Dinamitas''<ref name=FdM2019>{{cite web | url=http://www.thegladiatores.com/emotivo-homenaje-a-vampiro-canadiense-en-el-festival-de-mascaras/ | title=Emotivo homenaje a Vampiro Canadiense en el festival de m\u00e1scaras. | trans-title=Emotional homage to Canadian Vampire at the Festival of the Masks| date=June 17, 2019 | accessdate=August 8, 2019 | language=Spanish | work=The Gladiatores | first=Alfonso |last=Lizzaranga}}</ref>\n\n==Championships and accomplishments==\n*'''[[Consejo Mundial de Lucha Libre]]'''\n:*[[CMLL World Middleweight Championship]] ([[List of CMLL World Middleweight Champions#Title history|1 time]], current)<ref name=CuatreroMiddle>{{cite web | url=http://www.njpw.co.jp/card_result/130117 | title=NJPW presents CMLL Fantastica Mania 2018 CMLL\u4e16\u754c\u30df\u30c9\u30eb\u7d1a\u9078\u624b\u6a29\u8a66\u5408 | trans-title= NJPW Presents CMLL Fanastica Mania 2018 CMLL World Middleweight Championship |publisher=[[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]] | language=Japanese | date=January 19, 2018 | accessdate=January 19, 2018 }}</ref>\n:*[[CMLL Arena Coliseo Tag Team Championship]] ([[CMLL Arena Coliseo Tag Team Championship|1 time]]) \u2013 with [[Sans\u00f3n (wrestler)|Sans\u00f3n]]<ref name=NGD>{{cite web | url=http://www.mediotiempo.com/lucha-libre/2017/07/22/sanson-y-cuatrero-nuevos-campeones-de-la-arena-coliseo | title=Sans\u00f3n y Cuatrero, nuevos campeones de la Arena Coliseo | date=July 22, 2017 | accessdate=July 24, 2017 | work=MedioTiempo | language=Spanish | first=Apolo | last=Vald\u00e9s | trans-title=Sanson and Cuatrero, new champions of Arena Coliseo}}</ref>\n:*[[Mexican National Trios Championship]] ([[List of Mexican National Trios Champions#Title history|1 time]], current) \u2013 with Sans\u00f3n and [[Forastero]]<ref name=NGDTrios>{{cite web | url=http://www.mediotiempo.com/lucha-libre/2017/07/26/sanson-cuatrero-y-forastero-campeones-nacionales-de-tercias | title=Sans\u00f3n, Cuatrero y Forastero, campeones nacionales de tercias | date=July 26, 2017 | accessdate=July 26, 2017 | work=MedioTiempo | language=Spanish | trans-title=Sanson, Cuatrero and Forastero National Trios Champions}}</ref>\n:*Occidente Trios Championship (1 time, current) \u2013 with Sans\u00f3n and Forastero<ref name=DivinasLuchas/><ref name=OCCTrios>{{cite web | title=Occidente Trios Championship | publisher=cagematch |url=http://www.cagematch.net/?id=5&nr=2518 | accessdate=January 23, 2020}}</ref>\n:*''La Copa Dinastia'' (2017) \u2013 with Sans\u00f3n and Forastero<ref name=CopaDinastia2017>{{cite web | url=https://www.cagematch.net//?id=1&nr=187827 | title=CMLL Super Viernes | date=November 24, 2017 | accessdate=July 29, 2018 | work=CageMatch | language=German}}</ref>\n:*''[[Torneo de parejas familiares]]'' (2020) \u2013 with Sans\u00f3n<ref name=NGDFamiliares>{{cite web | url=https://superluchas.com/cmll-la-ngd-se-lleva-el-torneo-de-parejas-familiares-de-puebla/ | title=CMLL: La NGD se lleva el Torneo de Parejas Familiares de Puebla | author=Dark Angelita | date=February 25, 2020 | accessdate=February 26, 2020 | language=Spanish | work=[[S\u00faper Luchas]] | trans-title=CMLL: The NGD win the Family Tag Team Tournament in Puebla}}</ref>\n\n*'''''[[Pro Wrestling Illustrated]]'''''\n**Ranked #'''322''' of the best 500 singles wrestlers in the [[PWI 500]] in 2018<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cagematch.net/?id=97&nr=230#2018|title=Pro Wrestling Illustrated (PWI) 500 for 2018|accessdate=September 14, 2018|work=CageMatch}}</ref>\n\n==''Luchas de Apuestas'' record==\n{{See also|Lucha libre#Luchas de Apuestas|l1=Luchas de Apuestas}}\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" width=100%  style=\"text-align: center\"\n|-\n!style=\"background: #e3e3e3;\" width=20% scope=\"col\"|Winner (wager)\n!style=\"background: #e3e3e3;\" width=20% scope=\"col\"|Loser (wager)\n!style=\"background: #e3e3e3;\" width=20% scope=\"col\"|Location\n!style=\"background: #e3e3e3;\" width=20% scope=\"col\"|Event\n!style=\"background: #e3e3e3;\" width=15% scope=\"col\"|Date\n!class=\"unsortable\" style=\"background: #e3e3e3;\" width=5% scope=\"col\"|Notes\n|-\n|El Cuatrero and [[Sans\u00f3n (wrestler)|Sans\u00f3n]] (masks) || Los Centellas (I and II) || N/A || Live show || N/A || <ref name=DivinasLuchas/>\n|-\n|El Cuatrero (mask) || [[\u00c1ngel de Oro]] (mask) || [[Arena Mexico]] || ''[[Homenaje a Dos Leyendas (2018)|Homenaje a Dos Leyendas]]'' || {{dts|March 16, 2018}} || <ref name=AngelApuesta>{{cite web |url= https://ovaciones.com/cae-angel-de-oro |title= \u00a1Cae \u00c1ngel de Oro! |first= Arturo |last= Rosas Plata |date= March 17, 2018 |accessdate= June 23, 2018 |language= Spanish |publisher= Ovaciones | trans-title=The fall of \u00c1ngel de Oro!}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Consejo Mundial de Lucha Libre roster}}\n{{CMLL Arena Coliseo Tag Team Championship}}\n{{CMLL World Middleweight Championship}}\n{{Mexican National Trios Championship}}\n{{Portal bar|Biography|Mexico}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cuatrero, El}}\n[[Category:1996 births]]\n[[Category:Date of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Mexican male professional wrestlers]]\n[[Category:Masked wrestlers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox professional wrestler\n| name = El Cuatrero\n| image =El Cuatrero.jpg\n| image_size =\n| alt =\n| caption =El Cuatrero holding the [[CMLL World Middleweight Championship]] in the air, November 2018\n| birth_name = \n| birth_date = 1996\n| birth_place = Lagos de Moreno, Jalisco, Mexico<ref name=MedioIntro/>\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| resides =\n| spouse =\n| children =\n| family = {{Unbulleted list|[[Cien Caras]] (father)<ref name=MedioIntro/>|[[Sans\u00f3n (wrestler)|Sans\u00f3n]] (brother)<ref name=MedioIntro/>|[[M\u00e1scara A\u00f1o 2000]] (uncle)<ref name=MedioIntro/>|[[Universo 2000]] (uncle)<ref name=MedioIntro/>|[[Forastero]] (cousin)|[[Universo 2000 Jr.]] (cousin)|[[M\u00e1scara A\u00f1o 2000 Jr.]] (cousin)}}\n| alma_mater =\n| names ={{Unbulleted list|'''El Cuatrero'''|M\u00e1scara Universal}}\n| height = {{Convert|185|cm|ftin|abbr=on}}<ref name=DivinasLuchas/><!-- In Mexico they measure height in meters so that should be first -->\n| weight ={{convert|94|kg|lb|abbr=on}}<ref name=DivinasLuchas/><!--In Mexico they measure weight in kilograms so that should be first -->\n| billed =\n| trainer ={{Unbulleted list|[[Universo 2000]]<ref name=Starmedia/>|[[\u00daltimo Guerrero]]|[[Virus (wrestler)|Virus]]|[[Franco Colombo]]}}\n| debut =2010<ref name=MedioIntro/>\n| retired =\n| website =\n}}\n'''''El Cuatrero''''' (born 1996) is a Mexican ''[[Lucha libre|luchador]] enmascarado'', or [[wrestling mask|masked]] [[professional wrestler]] currently working for ''[[Consejo Mundial de Lucha Libre]]'' (CMLL) based in Mexico City. He is the son of ''lucha libre'' legend [[Cien Caras]] and the nephew of [[M\u00e1scara A\u00f1o 2000]] and [[Universo 2000]]. Cuatrero, his brother [[Sans\u00f3n (wrestler)|Sans\u00f3n]] and their cousin [[Forastero]] form a trio known as ''Nueva Generaci\u00f3n Dinamitas'' (\"New Generation Dynamites\"), the successor to ''[[Los Capos|Los Hermanos Dinamita]]'' (Cien Caras, M\u00e1scara A\u00f1o 2000 and Universo 2000). His real name is not a matter of public record, as is often the case with masked wrestlers in Mexico where their private lives are kept a secret from the wrestling fans.<ref name=Mondo>{{cite book | author= Madigan, Dan | title= Mondo Lucha Libre: the bizarre & honorable world of wild Mexican wrestling | publisher= HarperColins Publisher | year= 2007 | chapter = Okay... what is Lucha Libre? | pages = 29\u201340|isbn=978-0-06-085583-3}}</ref> His [[ring name]] is Spanish for \"The Horse thief\" or  \"The [[Cattle Rustler]]\", reflected in the cowboy-inspired ring gear and mask he wears during shows.\n\nEl Cuatrero is the current [[CMLL World Middleweight Champion]] and at one point held four championships simultaneously, which included the [[CMLL Arena Coliseo Tag Team Championship]] (with Sans\u00f3n), the [[Mexican National Trios Championship]] (with Sans\u00f3n and Forastero) and the Occidente Trios Championship (with Sans\u00f3n and Forastero). He won the mask of [[\u00c1ngel de Oro]] in the main event of CMLL's 2018 ''[[Homenaje a Dos Leyendas]]'' show on March&nbsp;16, 2018.\n\n==Personal life==\nEl Cuatrero was born in 1996, a son of [[professional wrestler]] Carmelo Reyes Gonz\u00e1lez, better known under the [[ring name]] [[Cien Caras]] (\"100 Faces\"). His older brother, known under the name [[Sans\u00f3n (wrestler)|Sans\u00f3n]] (\"[[Samson]]\") was born in 1994. His uncles Jes\u00fas (known as [[M\u00e1scara A\u00f1o 2000]]) and Andr\u00e9s ([[Universo 2000]]) were also professional wrestlers.<ref name=MondoFamily/> Several of their sons followed their fathers into professional wrestling, including [[Forastero]], [[Universo 2000 Jr.]] and [[M\u00e1scara A\u00f1o 2000 Jr.]]<ref>{{cite web | url= http://www.mediotiempo.com/mas-deportes/lucha-libre/noticias/2012/08/05/wagner-destapo-a-mascara-2000-jr | title= Wagner destap\u00f3 a M\u00e1scara 2000 Jr. | last=Rodr\u00edguez | first=Alejandro | date=August 5, 2012 | accessdate=February 19, 2013 | work=MedioTiempo | language=Spanish | trans-title=Wagner unmasks M\u00e1scara 2000 Jr.}}</ref> Initially, Carmelo Reyes did not want his sons to become professional wrestlers, wanting them to get an education instead. He reluctantly agreed that they could train for ''Lucha Libre'' with their uncle Andr\u00e9s, but only as a hobby. During their training, Carmelo noticed how serious they took it and reluctantly agreed with their choice to become professional wrestlers.<ref name=DivinasLuchas>{{cite web | url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Uz7nTR_jZSE | title=Divinas de la lucha Cuatrero y Sans\u00f3n | date=March 5, 2017 | accessdate=February 16, 2017 | first=Elisa | last=Tud\u00f3n | work=Divinas de la Luchas | language=Spanish | trans-title=Divine fighters Cuatrero and Sanson}}</ref>\n\nThere is a long tradition of wrestlers paying for the right to use a ring name in Mexican wrestling, including being allowed to portray a second or third-generation wrestler without being related to the originator.<ref name=MondoFamily>{{cite book|author=Madigan, Dan|title=Mondo Lucha a Go Go: the bizarre & honorable world of wild Mexican wrestling|publisher=[[HarperCollins]] Publisher|year=2007|chapter=A family affair|pages = 128\u2013132|isbn=978-0-06-085583-3}}</ref> It has been confirmed that wrestlers [[Cien Caras Jr.]] and [[El Hijo de Cien Caras]] are unrelated to the Reyes family, while it is unclear if [[Hijo de M\u00e1scara A\u00f1o 2000]] is a blood relative or a purely fictional relative.<ref name=Adios>{{cite web|url=http://www.record.com.mx/blog/el-hijo-del-santo/2010-12-02/el-adios-del-hijo-de-cien-caras |title=El adi\u00f3s del Hijo de Cien Caras |authorlink=El Hijo del Santo | first=El | last=Hijo del Santo |date=December 2, 2010 |accessdate=February 19, 2013 |publisher=R\u00e9cord.com |language=Spanish |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101204113931/http://www.record.com.mx/blog/el-hijo-del-santo/2010-12-02/el-adios-del-hijo-de-cien-caras |archivedate=December 4, 2010 |trans-title=Goodbye to El Hijo de Cien Caras}}</ref> Reyes later stated that he allowed the \"Cien Caras\" name to be rented by other wrestlers as his sons were very young and might not want to become professional wrestlers.<ref name=MedioIntro/>\n\n==Professional wrestling career==\n[[File:Nueva Generacion Dinamitas.jpg|thumb|left|[[Sans\u00f3n (wrestler)|Sans\u00f3n]], El Cuatrero and [[Forastero]] outside the ring in November 2018]]\nWhile the El Cuatrero name was first used in 2014, Sans\u00f3n said they made their in-ring debut around the year 2010 and worked locally in Lagos de Moreno, while finishing school.<ref name=MedioIntro>{{cite web | url=http://www.mediotiempo.com/mas-deportes/lucha-libre/noticias/2015/12/01/herederos-de-cien-caras-cerca-de-debut-en-arena-mexico | title=Herederos de Cien Caras cerca de debut en Arena M\u00e9xico | date=December 1, 2015 | accessdate=February 16, 2018 | language=Spanish | work=MedioTiempo | first=Apolo | last=Vald\u00e9s | trans-title=The successors to Cien Casas make their debut in Arena Mexico}}</ref> In an interview Cuatrero said that he wrestled briefly as \"M\u00e1scara Universal\", but his father did not like the name and suggested the name \"El Cuatrero\", Spanish for \"The [[Cattle rustler]] instead. This was inspired by the cowboy gimmick that his father and his uncles had used.<ref name=Starmedia>{{cite web | url=http://www.starmedia.com/noticias/sanson-cuatrero-reviviran-memoria-cien-caras-en-arena-mexico/ | title=Sans\u00f3n Y Cuatrero Revivir\u00e1n Memoria De Cien Caras En La Arena M\u00e9xico | date=December 28, 2015 | accessdate=February 16, 2018 | work=[[Starmedia|StarMedia]] | language=Spanish | trans-title=Sanson and Cuatrero revieve the memory of Cien Caras in Arena Mexico | archivedate=July 31, 2018  | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180731125041/https://www.starmedia.com/noticias/sanson-cuatrero-reviviran-memoria-cien-caras-en-arena-mexico}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.elsoldemexico.com.mx/deportes/Sans\u00f3n-y-Cuatrero-los-\u201cNuevos-Dinamita\u201d-198235.html | title=Sans\u00f3n y Cuatrero, los \"Nuevos Dinamita\" | date=October 23, 2015 | accessdate=February 16, 2018 | language=Spanish | work=El Sol del Mexico | first=Armando | last=Isa\u00eds | trans-title=Sanson and Cuatrero, the \"New Dynamites\"}}</ref> During their time working locally in Lagos de Moreno, the duo won their first ''[[Lucha de Apuestas]]'', or bet match, when they defeated Los Centellas (I and II) and unmasked the duo.<ref name=DivinasLuchas/>\n\n===Consejo Mundial de Lucha Libre (2014\u2013present)===\nThe Reyes  brothers worked locally until early 2014, when they began working in Guadalajara for the local ''[[Consejo Mundial de Lucha Libre]]'' (CMLL) promoters in Arena Coliseo. They trained at the CMLL wrestling school under [[\u00daltimo Guerrero]], [[Virus (wrestler)|Virus]] and [[Franco Colombo]].<ref name=Starmedia/> The Reyes brothers made their CMLL debut on March&nbsp;25, 2014, where they, along with Universo 2000, lost to the trio of [[Blue Panther]], [[Sagrado (wrestler)|Sagrado]], and [[Valiente (wrestler)|Valiente]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.cagematch.net//?id=1&nr=108892 | title=CMLL Guadalajara Martes | date=March 25, 2014 | accessdate=February 18, 2018 | work=CageMatch| language=German}}</ref> While working in Guadalajara, El Cuatrero and Sans\u00f3n competed in a tournament to determine the number one contenders for the local Occidente Tag Team Championship, but they were eliminated by the team of Flash and Flash II.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.cagematch.net//?id=1&nr=124225 | title=CMLL Guadalajara Viernes | date=January 30, 2015 | accessdate=July 29, 2018 | work=CageMatch| language=German}}</ref> The brothers teamed up with Jocker. The winners would be crowned the new Occidente Trios Champions. The team made it to the final match of the tournament but were defeated by Furia Roja, Mr. Trueno, and Ray Trueno.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.cagematch.net//?id=1&nr=128976 | title=CMLL Guadalajara Domingos | date=March 5, 2015 | accessdate=July 29, 2018 | work=CageMatch| language=German}}</ref> On November&nbsp;11, 2015, Cuatrero and Sans\u00f3n teamed up with their cousin Forastero and won the Occidente Trios Championship.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.cagematch.net//?id=1&nr=140036 | title=LLE | date=November 11, 2015 | accessdate=July 29, 2018 | work=CageMatch| language=German}}</ref>\n\nOn January&nbsp;5, 2017, El Cuatrero worked his first CMLL match in Mexico City in the company's main venue. He participated in the 2017 version of ''[[La Copa Junior]]'' but was eliminated from the tournament before the finals.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.mediotiempo.com/mas-deportes/lucha-libre/noticias/2016/01/06/puma-finalista-de-la-copa-jr-del-cmll | title=Puma, finalista de la Copa Jr. del CMLL | date=January 6, 2015 | accessdate=January 10, 2016 | work=MedioTiempo | language=Spanish | trans-title=Puma finalist in the CMLL La Copa Jr.}}</ref> At that point, the Reyes brothers began being referred to as ''Nueva Generacion Dinamitas'' (Spanish for \"New Generation Dynamites\"; NGD)\u2014a reference to their heritage. On March&nbsp;18, 2016, ''Nueva Generacion Dinamitas'' worked their first major show for CMLL, defeating [[Soberano Jr.]] and [[Oro Jr.]] in the opening match of that year's ''[[Homenaje a Dos Leyendas (2016)|Homenaje A Dos Leyendas]]'' show.<ref name=DosLeyendas2016SL>{{cite web | url=http://superluchas.com/cmll-homenaje-a-dos-leyendas-cobertura-y-resultados-21032016/ | title=CMLL \"Homenaje a Dos Leyendas\" \u2013 Cobertura y Resultados \u2013 21/03/2016 \u2013 M\u00e1ximo Sexy y Negro Casas, pelones | author=Dark Angelita | date=March 18, 2016 | accessdate=March 19, 2016 | work=[[S\u00faper Luchas]] | language=Spanish | trans-title= CMLL \"Homage to Two Legends \u2013 Coverage and results \u2013 21/02/1016 \u2013 M\u00e1ximo Sexy and Negro Casas bald}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://es-us.deportes.yahoo.com/fotos/homenaje-a-dos-leyendas-lucha-libre-arena-m%C3%A9xico-viernes-18-de-marzo-de-2016-slideshow/ | title=Homenaje a Dos Leyendas, Lucha Libre Arena M\u00e9xico, Viernes 18 de Marzo de 2016 | date=March 19, 2016 | accessdate=March 19, 2016 | publisher=[[Yahoo!]] | work=Yahoo! Deportes | first=Gonzalo | last= L\u00f3pez Peralta}}</ref> CMLL decided to have both El Cuatrero and Sans\u00f3n participate in their annual ''[[Torneo Gran Alternativa (2016)|Torneo Gran Alternativa]]'' (\"Great Alternativa Tournament\") where younger wrestlers team up with established veteran wrestlers. El Cuatrero was paired with [[Rey Bucanero]], but the duo lost to [[Trit\u00f3n (wrestler)|Trit\u00f3n]] and [[M\u00edstico II|M\u00edstico]] in the first round.<ref name=Medio2016BlockA>{{cite web | url=http://www.mediotiempo.com/mas-deportes/lucha-libre/noticias/2016/03/23/rey-escorpion-y-fujin-por-la-gran-alternativa | title=Rey Escorpi\u00f3n y Fuj\u00edn, por la Gran Alternativa | date=March 23, 2016 | accessdate=March 23, 2016 | work=MedioTiempo | language=Spanish | trans-title=Rey Escorpi\u00f3n and Fuj\u00edn go for the Gran Alternativa}}</ref> A year later, El Cuatrero was teamed up with his uncle M\u00e1scara A\u00f1o 2000 for the 2017 version of the ''[[Torneo Gran Alternativa (2017)|Torneo Gran Alternativa]]'',  but like the 2016 tournament, El Cuatrero did not make it past the first round as the team lost to [[Esfinge]] and [[Atlantis (wrestler)|Atlantis]].<ref name=2017BlockAF4W>{{cite web | url=http://www.f4wonline.com/mexico/cmll-arena-mexico-results-la-gran-alternativa-tournament-begins-236681| title=CMLL Arena Mexico Results: La Gran Alternativa tournament begins | date=June 4, 2017 | accessdate=June 11, 2017 | work=Wrestling Observer Figure Four Online | first=Chris | last=Aiken}}</ref> While El Cuatrero's first years on the main roster had seen little success, July 2017 proved a turning point in how ''Nueva Generacion Dinamitas'' was booked. El Cuatrero and Sans\u00f3n defeated [[Black Terry]] and [[Negro Navarro]] to win the [[CMLL Arena Coliseo Tag Team Championship]], CMLL's second-highest ranked tag team championship.<ref name=NGD/> Three days later the trio defeated ''[[Los Hijos del Infierno]]'' ([[Ephesto]], [[Luciferno]], and [[Mephisto (wrestler)|Mephisto]]) to win the [[Mexican National Trios Championship]], making Ephesto a triple championship.<ref name=NGDTrios/> The trio would win CMLL's ''La Copa Dinastia'', defeating the trios of Blue Panther, [[Blue Panther Jr.]], [[The Panther (wrestler)|The Panter]] and then [[Dragon Lee (wrestler)|Dragon Lee]], M\u00edstico, and [[Comandante Pierroth|Pierroth]].<ref name=CopaDinastia2017/> \n\nOn January&nbsp;19, 2018, as part of the annual [[Fantastica Mania 2018|2018 Fantastica Mania]] tour of Japan, El Cuatrero defeated [[\u00c1ngel de Oro]] to win the [[CMLL World Middleweight Championship]].<ref name=CuatreroMiddle/> The match and championship change was the beginning of a long-running storyline feud between El Cuatrero and \u00c1ngel de Oro, where challenges for a ''Lucha de Apuestas'' match soon followed.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.mediotiempo.com/lucha-libre/2018/02/07/angel-de-oro-y-cuatrero-se-jugaran-las-mascaras-en-homenaje-a-dos-leyendas | language=Spanish | accessdate=July 30, 2018 | date=February 7, 2019 | work=MedioTiempo | title=\u00c1ngel de Oro y Cuatrero se jugaran las mascaras en Homenaje a Dos Leyendas | trans-title=\u00c1ngel de Oro, fighting for the asks at Homage to Two Legends}}</ref> On February&nbsp;14, 2018, ''Nueva Generacion Dinamitas'' announced they were giving up the CMLL Arena Coliseo Tag Team Championship. Their storyline was that they were focusing on winning the [[CMLL World Tag Team Championship]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://twitter.com/CMLL_OFICIAL/status/964177915343724550 | title=Sans\u00f3n y Cuatrero renuncian al Campeonato de Parejas de la Arena Coliseo. | trans-title=Sans\u00f3n and Cuatrero give up the Arena Colise Tag Team Championship |date=February 15, 2018 | accessdate=March 11, 2018 | author=CMLL | publisher=[[Twitter]] | language=Spanish}}</ref> The storyline feud between El Cuatrero and \u00c1ngel de Oro reached its peak at the 2018 ''[[Homenaje a Dos Leyendas (2018)|Homenaje a Dos Leyendas]]'' show, where both competitors put their mask on the line in the main event match of the night. El Cuatrero defeated \u00c1ngel de Oro two falls to one, forcing him to remove his mask as per ''lucha libre'' tradition.<ref name=AngelApuesta/> El Cuatrero would later make his first and second successful defense of the CMLL World Middleweight Championship against \u00c1ngel de Oro.<ref name=CMLLMiddle>{{cite web | url=https://www.cagematch.net//?id=5&nr=93&page=5&reign=19 | title= CMLL World Middleweight Championship >> Title Reigns >> 19.01.2018 - Today: El Cuatrero| accessdate=March 4, 2020 | work=CageMatch}}</ref> At the [[CMLL 85th Anniversary Show]], the Dinamitas defeated Atlantis, El Soberano Jr., and Mistico as part of CMLL's most important show of the year.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.f4wonline.com/mexico/cmll-85th-aniversario-live-results-hair-vs-hair-tag-team-main-event-265781 | title=CMLL 85. Aniversario live results: hair vs. hair tag team main event | work=[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter|Wrestling Observer Figure Four Online]] | date=September 14, 2018 | accessdate=September 15, 2018 | first=Chris | last=Aiken}}</ref> On November&nbsp;6, 2018, Cuatrero made his third successful middleweight championship defense as he defeated [[Tit\u00e1n (wrestler)|Tit\u00e1n]].<ref name=CMLLMiddle/>\n\n2019 was the first year that the three members of Nueva Generaci\u00f3n Dinamitas participated in the annual [[Fantastica Mania 2019|Fantastica Mania]] tour of Japan, capping off the tour with a successful championship defense against \u00c1ngel de Oro, Atlantis, and Tit\u00e1n on its last day.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.f4wonline.com/japan/njpwcmll-fantastica-mania-results-my-dad-heel-wrestler-match-275026 | title=NJPW/CMLL Fantastica Mania results: 'My Dad is a heel wrestler' match | date=January 21, 2019 | accessdate=January 21, 2019 | work=[[Wrestling Observer Newsletter]] | first=Ethan | last=Renner}}</ref> 2019 also marked the first year that El Cuatrero participated in the [[CMLL Universal Championship (2019)|Universal Championship]], a tournament where all 16 participants held a championship recognized by CMLL. In the opening round. he defeated perennial rival Soberano Jr. before losing to \u00daltimo Guerrero in the quarterfinals.<ref name=BlockBOvaciones>{{cite web | url=https://ovaciones.com/vence-al-maestro/ | title=\u00a1Vence al maestro! | trans-title=defeating the master | date=February 9, 2019 | accessdate=February 9, 2019 | first=Arturo | last=Rosas Platas | language=Spanish | work=Ovaciones}}</ref><ref name=BlockBMarca>{{cite web | url=https://www.marca.com/claro-mx/otros-deportes/lucha-libre/2019/02/09/5c5e6f62268e3e8f7c8b45a1.html | work=Marca Claro | title=Niebla Roja se impone en la segunda fase del torneo Campe\u00f3n Universal 2019 | trans-title=Niebla Roja looks imposing in the second phase of the 2019 Universal Championship | date=February 9, 2019 | accessdate=February 9, 2019 | language=Spanish}}</ref> For the 2019 ''[[CMLL Torneo Nacional de Parejas Incre\u00edbles (2019)|Torneo Nacional de Parejas Incre\u00edbles]]'' (\"National Incredible Teams Tournament), Cuatrero was paired up with M\u00edstico, as a ''[[Heel (professional wrestling)|rudo]]'' (The \"bad guy\") and a ''[[Face (professional wrestling)|tecnico]]'' (the \"Good guy\") team up for the event. The odd couple defeated [[Hechicero]] and [[Stuka Jr.]], then Atlantis and Negro Casas, before ultimately losing to \u00daltimo Guerrero and Volador Jr. in the semifinals.<ref name=Increibles2019B>{{cite web | url= https://www.20minutos.com.mx/deportes/noticia/ultimo-guerrero-y-volador-jr-van-a-final-de-torneo-increible-505260/0/ | title= \u00daltimo Guerrero y Volador Jr. van a final de \"Torneo incre\u00edble\"|trans-title=\u00daltimo Guerrero and Volador Jr. goes to the finals of the \u201cIncredible Tournament\u201d| language=Spanish | work=[[20 Minutos]] | author=Notimex | date=April 20, 2019 | accessdate=May 17, 2019}}</ref><ref name=Ovaciones2019B>{{cite web | url=https://ovaciones.com/volador-y-guerrero-a-la-final/ | title=Volador y Guerrero a la final | trans-title=Volador and Guerrero in the finals | language=Spanish | accessdate=May 17, 2019 | date=April 20, 2019  | work=Ovacones | first=Arturo | last=Rosas Plata}}</ref> As part of the 66th&nbsp;anniversary of Arena Puebla, NGD successfully defended the Mexican National Trios Championship against ''[[Los Ingobernables]]'' ([[El Terrible]], [[La Bestia del Ring]], and [[Rush (wrestler)|Rush]]), in what was their tenth overall championship defense.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.cagematch.net//?id=5&nr=532&page=5&reign=41 | title=Mexican National Trios Championship >> 25.07.2017 - today: La Sangre Dinamita (El Cuatrero, Forasteo & Sanson) | work=CageMatch | accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref> In December, El Cuatrero made his fourth successful defense of the CMLL World Middleweight Championship as he defeated [[Car\u00edstico]] on December&nbsp;12.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.cagematch.net//?id=1&nr=250178 | title=CMLL Sabados De Coliseo | date=December 12, 2019 | accessdate=March 31, 2020 | work=CageMatch}}</ref>\n\nThe 2020 ''[[Sin Piedad (2020)|Sin Piedad]]'' show offered Cuatrero the opportunity to become a quadruple champion as he and Sans\u00f3n challenged M\u00edstico and Car\u00edstico for the CMLL World Tag Team Championship but lost the match.<ref name=SP2020Medio>{{cite web | url=https://www.mediotiempo.com/lucha-libre/cmll/espiritu-negro-fue-desenmascarado-por-principe-diamante | title=Cay\u00f3 la primera m\u00e1scara en el 2020 dentro del CMLL; Esp\u00edritu Negro revel\u00f3 su rostro | trans-title=The first mask loss in CMLL of 2020; Espiritu Negro revealed his face | language=Spanish | date=January 2, 2020 | accessdate=January 2, 2020 | work=MedioTiempo}}</ref> During the 2020 [[Fantastica Mania 2020|Fantastica Mania]] tour, Cuatrero and his brother participated in the [[List of CMLL tag team tournaments#2020 Family tag team tournament|family tag team tournament]], where they ended up defeating ''Los Hermanos Chavez'' (\u00c1ngel de Oro and Niebla Roja) in the finals.<ref name=FM20Jan19>{{cite web | url=https://www.njpw.co.jp/tornament/220096?showResult=1 | title=NJPW presents CMLL Fantastica Mania 2020 | language=Japanese | date=January 17, 2020 | accessdate=January 17, 2020 | work=[[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]]}}</ref> On the final day of the tour, January&nbsp;20, NGD successfully defended the Mexican National Trios Championship against ''Los Hermanos Chavez'' and Tit\u00e1n.<ref name=NJPWFM202Jan20>{{cite web | url=https://www.njpw.co.jp/tornament/220098?showResult=1 | title=NJPW presents CMLL Fantastica Mania 2020 | date=January 20, 2020 | accessdate=January 20, 2020 | work=[[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]] | language=Japanese}}</ref> On February&nbsp;24, 2020, El Cuatrero and Sans\u00f3n won the ''[[#Torneo de parejas familiares|Torneo de parejas familiares]]'' (\"Family Team Tournament\") as they defeated the uncle/nephew team of Rey Bucanero and [[Drone (wrestler)|Drone]] in the first round, the father/son team of [[Euforia (wrestler)|Euforia]] and Soberano Jr. in the second round, and finally the [[Gran Guerrero]]/\u00daltimo Guerrero brothers in the finals.<ref name=NGDFamiliares/><ref name=LuchaCentral/>\n\n===Independent circuit (2014\u2013current)===\nWhile working for CMLL, Cuatrero, like all CMLL workes, is allowed to take independent circuit bookings on days he is not needed by CMLL or arranged through CMLL. On February 19, 2017, Cuatrero and Sans\u00f3n unsuccessfully challenged Black Terry and Negro Navarro for the CMLL Arena Coliseo Tag Team Championship on a ''Lucha Memes'' show in Puebla.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.cagematch.net//?id=1&nr=173059 | title=Lucha Memes | date=February 19, 2017 | accessdate=February 4, 2020 | work=CageMatch}}</ref> NGD also successfully defended the Mexican National Tag Team Championship against Los Kamikazes del Aire (Alas de Acero, [[Aramis]], and Iron Kid) at a subsequent ''Lucha Memes'' show.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.cagematch.net//?id=1&nr=192320 | title=Lucha Memes Chairo 12 | date=May 2, 2018| accessdate=February 4, 2020 | work=CageMatch}}</ref> \n\nAs part of CMLL's collaboration with [[The Crash Lucha Libre]], Nueva Generaci\u00f3n Dinamitas has performed on several The Crash shows over the years. In their initial appearance for The Crash, Nueva Generaci\u00f3n Dinamitas lost to [[La Rebeli\u00f3n Amarilla]] ([[Bestia 666]], [[Jacob Fatu]] and [[Mecha Wolf 450]]).<ref>{{cite web | url=https://tjsports.com.mx/se-termina-la-rebelion/ |title=\u00a1Se Termina \u2018La Rebeli\u00f3n\u2019! | trans-title=The end of \"The Rebellion\" | date=September 8, 2018 | accessdate=March 3, 2020 | language=Spanish | work=TJ Sports}}</ref> The team returned to The Crash for their [[The Crash VII Aniversario|VII Anniversary Show]] show, where they lost to ''Los Lucha Bros'' ([[Pentag\u00f3n Jr.|Penta El 0M]] and [[F\u00e9nix (wrestler)|The King]]) in a match for [[The Crash Tag Team Championship]] that also included [[Reno Scum]] (Adam Thornstowe and Luster the Legend).<ref name=LuchaCentral>{{cite web | url=https://www.luchacentral.com/resultados-aniversario-vii-the-crash-espanol/ | title=\u00a1Resultados Aniversario VII THE CRASH ! Espanol | trans-title=Results of the Crash VII Anniversary! Spanish | date=November 3, 2018 | accessdate=November 4, 2018 | first=Miguel | last=Pe\u00f1a | work=Lucha Central | language=Spanish}}</ref><ref name=LuchaWorld>{{cite web | url=http://www.luchaworld.com/?p=86983 | title=Lucha Report for 11/4/18 | date=November 4, 2018 | accessdate=November 4, 2018 | first=Alfredo | last=Esparza | work=Lucha World}}</ref> They returned to The Crash in December 2018, losing to Bestia 666 and [[Garza Jr.]] in the main event.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://tjsports.com.mx/garza-jr-y-bestia-666-demostraron-porque-son-la-cara-de-the-crash-lucha-libre/| title=Garza Jr. Y Bestia 666 Demostraron Porque Son La Cara De The Crash Lucha Libre | trans-title=Garza Jr. Y Bestia 666 demonstrate why they are the face of The Crash Lucha Libre | work=TJ Sports | language=Spanish | accessdate=March 4, 2020 | date=December 1, 2018}}</ref> In 2019 Cuatrero and Sans\u00f3n worked an extended storyline against ''[[Los Traumas]]'' ([[Trauma I]] and [[Trauma II]]) in The Crash. In June Sans\u00f3n was forced to team up with Trauma I to face Cuatrero and Trauma I in a ''[[relevos incre\u00edbles]]'' (\"incredible pairs\" match), where the regular partners refused to wrestle against each other. In the end, Sans\u00f3n and Trauma I after Trauma II hit El Cuatrero during the match.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.cagematch.net//?id=1&nr=231526 | title=The Crash | date=June 15, 2019 | accessdate=March 4, 2020 | work=CageMatch}}</ref> This was followed by a tag team match where NGD defeated Los Traumas by disqualification as part of their ongoing storyline.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.cagematch.net//?id=1&nr=233101 | title=FCP Project Mexico| date=September 7, 2019 | accessdate=March 4, 2020 | work=CageMatch}}</ref>\n\nOn June 16, 2019, Cuatrero, Forastero, and Sans\u00f3n appeared at International Wrestling Revolution Group's annual [[Festival de las M\u00e1scaras (2019)|Festival de las M\u00e1scaras]] show. The trio defeated their cousin M\u00e1scara A\u00f1o 2000 Jr., teaming with Capo del Sur and Capo del Norte, who both use ring characters inspired by the original ''Los Dinamitas''<ref name=FdM2019>{{cite web | url=http://www.thegladiatores.com/emotivo-homenaje-a-vampiro-canadiense-en-el-festival-de-mascaras/ | title=Emotivo homenaje a Vampiro Canadiense en el festival de m\u00e1scaras. | trans-title=Emotional homage to Canadian Vampire at the Festival of the Masks| date=June 17, 2019 | accessdate=August 8, 2019 | language=Spanish | work=The Gladiatores | first=Alfonso |last=Lizzaranga}}</ref>\n\n==Championships and accomplishments==\n*'''[[Consejo Mundial de Lucha Libre]]'''\n:*[[CMLL World Middleweight Championship]] ([[List of CMLL World Middleweight Champions#Title history|1 time]], current)<ref name=CuatreroMiddle>{{cite web | url=http://www.njpw.co.jp/card_result/130117 | title=NJPW presents CMLL Fantastica Mania 2018 CMLL\u4e16\u754c\u30df\u30c9\u30eb\u7d1a\u9078\u624b\u6a29\u8a66\u5408 | trans-title= NJPW Presents CMLL Fanastica Mania 2018 CMLL World Middleweight Championship |publisher=[[New Japan Pro-Wrestling]] | language=Japanese | date=January 19, 2018 | accessdate=January 19, 2018 }}</ref>\n:*[[CMLL Arena Coliseo Tag Team Championship]] ([[CMLL Arena Coliseo Tag Team Championship|1 time]]) \u2013 with [[Sans\u00f3n (wrestler)|Sans\u00f3n]]<ref name=NGD>{{cite web | url=http://www.mediotiempo.com/lucha-libre/2017/07/22/sanson-y-cuatrero-nuevos-campeones-de-la-arena-coliseo | title=Sans\u00f3n y Cuatrero, nuevos campeones de la Arena Coliseo | date=July 22, 2017 | accessdate=July 24, 2017 | work=MedioTiempo | language=Spanish | first=Apolo | last=Vald\u00e9s | trans-title=Sanson and Cuatrero, new champions of Arena Coliseo}}</ref>\n:*[[Mexican National Trios Championship]] ([[List of Mexican National Trios Champions#Title history|1 time]], current) \u2013 with Sans\u00f3n and [[Forastero]]<ref name=NGDTrios>{{cite web | url=http://www.mediotiempo.com/lucha-libre/2017/07/26/sanson-cuatrero-y-forastero-campeones-nacionales-de-tercias | title=Sans\u00f3n, Cuatrero y Forastero, campeones nacionales de tercias | date=July 26, 2017 | accessdate=July 26, 2017 | work=MedioTiempo | language=Spanish | trans-title=Sanson, Cuatrero and Forastero National Trios Champions}}</ref>\n:*Occidente Trios Championship (1 time, current) \u2013 with Sans\u00f3n and Forastero<ref name=DivinasLuchas/><ref name=OCCTrios>{{cite web | title=Occidente Trios Championship | publisher=cagematch |url=http://www.cagematch.net/?id=5&nr=2518 | accessdate=January 23, 2020}}</ref>\n:*''La Copa Dinastia'' (2017) \u2013 with Sans\u00f3n and Forastero<ref name=CopaDinastia2017>{{cite web | url=https://www.cagematch.net//?id=1&nr=187827 | title=CMLL Super Viernes | date=November 24, 2017 | accessdate=July 29, 2018 | work=CageMatch | language=German}}</ref>\n:*''[[Torneo de parejas familiares]]'' (2020) \u2013 with Sans\u00f3n<ref name=NGDFamiliares>{{cite web | url=https://superluchas.com/cmll-la-ngd-se-lleva-el-torneo-de-parejas-familiares-de-puebla/ | title=CMLL: La NGD se lleva el Torneo de Parejas Familiares de Puebla | author=Dark Angelita | date=February 25, 2020 | accessdate=February 26, 2020 | language=Spanish | work=[[S\u00faper Luchas]] | trans-title=CMLL: The NGD win the Family Tag Team Tournament in Puebla}}</ref>\n\n*'''''[[Pro Wrestling Illustrated]]'''''\n**Ranked #'''322''' of the best 500 singles wrestlers in the [[PWI 500]] in 2018<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cagematch.net/?id=97&nr=230#2018|title=Pro Wrestling Illustrated (PWI) 500 for 2018|accessdate=September 14, 2018|work=CageMatch}}</ref>\n\n==''Luchas de Apuestas'' record==\n{{See also|Lucha libre#Luchas de Apuestas|l1=Luchas de Apuestas}}\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" width=100%  style=\"text-align: center\"\n|-\n!style=\"background: #e3e3e3;\" width=20% scope=\"col\"|Winner (wager)\n!style=\"background: #e3e3e3;\" width=20% scope=\"col\"|Loser (wager)\n!style=\"background: #e3e3e3;\" width=20% scope=\"col\"|Location\n!style=\"background: #e3e3e3;\" width=20% scope=\"col\"|Event\n!style=\"background: #e3e3e3;\" width=15% scope=\"col\"|Date\n!class=\"unsortable\" style=\"background: #e3e3e3;\" width=5% scope=\"col\"|Notes\n|-\n|El Cuatrero and [[Sans\u00f3n (wrestler)|Sans\u00f3n]] (masks) || Los Centellas (I and II) || N/A || Live show || N/A || <ref name=DivinasLuchas/>\n|-\n|El Cuatrero (mask) || [[\u00c1ngel de Oro]] (mask) || [[Arena Mexico]] || ''[[Homenaje a Dos Leyendas (2018)|Homenaje a Dos Leyendas]]'' || {{dts|March 16, 2018}} || <ref name=AngelApuesta>{{cite web |url= https://ovaciones.com/cae-angel-de-oro |title= \u00a1Cae \u00c1ngel de Oro! |first= Arturo |last= Rosas Plata |date= March 17, 2018 |accessdate= June 23, 2018 |language= Spanish |publisher= Ovaciones | trans-title=The fall of \u00c1ngel de Oro!}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Consejo Mundial de Lucha Libre roster}}\n{{CMLL Arena Coliseo Tag Team Championship}}\n{{CMLL World Middleweight Championship}}\n{{Mexican National Trios Championship}}\n{{Portal bar|Biography|Mexico}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cuatrero, El}}\n[[Category:1996 births]]\n[[Category:Date of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Mexican male professional wrestlers]]\n[[Category:Masked wrestlers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "Twofingered Typist", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eIndependent circuit (2014\u2013current):wording; spacing; clarification; fixed citation per WPMOS:No Caps; punctuation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/El_Cuatrero"}
{"title_page": "Seaslug (missile)", "text_new": "{{Infobox weapon\n|is_missile=yes\n|is_UK=yes\n| image= Sea Slug missile.png\n| image_size = 300\n|caption=Seaslug Mk. II missile\n|name=Seaslug\n|type=surface-to-air missile\n|origin=UK\n|era=Cold War\n|launch_platform=Ship\n|target=Aircraft\n|manufacturer=[[Armstrong Whitworth]]\n|design_date=Mark 1; 1961 <br/>Mark 2; 1965\n|production_date=\n|service=1961 - 1991\n|used_by=UK ([[Royal Navy]]), Chile\n|wars=[[Falklands War]]\n|spec_type=Anti-aircraft\n|diameter=Mk.1; 0.42 m <br/> Mk.2; 0.41 m\n|wingspan=1.44 m\n|length=Mk.1; 6.0 m <br/> Mk.2; 6.1 m\n|weight=Mk.1; 2,080 kg <br/> Mk.2; 2,384 kg\n|speed=Mk.1; {{convert|685|mi/h|km/h|abbr=on}} <br/> Mk.2; {{convert|1370|mi/h|km/h|abbr=on}}\n|vehicle_range=Mk.1; {{convert|30000|yd|m}} <br/> Mk.2; {{convert|35000|yd|m}}\n|ceiling=Mk.1; {{convert|55000|ft|m}} <br/> Mk.2; {{convert|65000|ft|m}}\n|filling=Mk.1; {{convert|200|lb|abbr=on}} blast <br/> Mk.2; [[continuous-rod warhead]]\n|engine=4 solid fuel jettisoned boosters & solid fuel [[sustainer rocket|sustainer]]\n|steering=control surface\n|guidance=[[Beam riding]]\n|variants= Mark 1, Mark 2\n|fuze=Mk.1; Radio proximity & impact<br/>Mk.2; Infra-red proximity\n|number=\n}}\n[[File:Armstrong Whitworth Seaslug missile.jpg|thumb|Seaslug on display at [[Wickenby Aerodrome]], Lincolnshire, UK]]\n'''Seaslug''' was a first-generation [[surface-to-air missile]] designed by [[Armstrong Whitworth]] (later part of the [[Hawker Siddeley]] group) for use by the [[Royal Navy]]. Tracing its history as far back as 1943, it came into operational service in 1961 and was still in use at the time of the [[Falklands War]] in 1982.\n\nSeaslug was intended to engage high-flying targets such as reconnaissance aircraft or bombers before they could launch stand-off weapons. It was only fitted to the Royal Navy's eight [[County-class destroyer]]s which were designed around the missile system.  Later improvements meant that it could also be used against ships. Seaslug was only fired in anger once as an anti-aircraft missile, from {{HMS|Antrim|D18|6}} during the Falklands War, but missed its target. It was also used for surface bombardment.\n\nSeaslug's medium-range role was to be supplanted by a very long-range missile known as [[Blue Envoy]], but this was passed over in favour of a new medium-range system, [[Sea Dart]]. Sea Dart entered service in 1973 on the [[Type 82 destroyer]]s and replaced Seaslug during the 1980s as the {{sclass2-|County|destroyer}}s were removed from service.\n\n==Development==\n===Initial concept===\nIn 1943, the German ''[[Luftwaffe]]'' began the use of [[anti-shipping missile]]s and guided bombs in the Mediterranean Ocean during Allied operations against Italy. These weapons were released outside of [[anti-aircraft gun]] range, which meant that any operations lacking complete [[air superiority]] would be open to attack with little response by the ships.{{sfn|Friedman|2012|p=197}} On 16 March 1944 the first meeting of the \"Guided Anti-Aircraft Projectile Committee\", or GAP Committee, was held.{{sfn|Grove|2004|p=193}}\n\nThe [[Admiralty Signals and Radar Establishment|Admiralty Signals Establishment]] (ASE), in charge of the Navy's [[radar]] development, was working on new radars featuring [[radar lock-on]] that allowed them to accurately track aircraft at long range. This was part of the LRS.1 [[fire-control system]] that allowed large dual-purpose guns to attack bombers at long range.{{sfn|Harding|2005|p=254}} A contemporary [[British Army]] project at Cossors, [[Brakemine]], was working on a system to allow a missile to keep itself centred within a radar beam, a concept known today as [[beam riding]]. The Navy decided to combine the two concepts, using the LRS.1's Type 909 radar with a new missile that differed from Brakemine primarily in requiring longer range and being more robust for shipborne use.{{sfn|Friedman|2012|p=197}}\n\nIn December 1944, GAP put out a Naval Staff Target for a new anti-aircraft weapon,{{sfn|Grove|2004|p=193}} capable of attacking targets at altitudes up to {{convert|50,000|ft|m|abbr=on}} and speeds of up to {{convert|700|mph|abbr=on}}.{{sfn|Grove|2004|p=194}} This project was briefly known as LOPGAP, short for \"Liquid Oxygen and Petrol Guided Anti-aircraft Projectile\",{{sfn|Twigge|1993|p=246}} but soon moved from petrol to [[methanol]] which made the \"LOP\" inaccurate, and the name accordingly changed simply to GAP,{{sfn|Morton|1989|p=209}} and then Seaslug. Efforts{{by whom|date=April 2020}} to change the name to \"Triumph\"{{why|date=April 2020}} failed.{{sfn|Grove|2004|p=194}}\n\n===LOPGAP===\nThe [[Fairey Aviation Company]] was at this time working on a missile project for the Ministry of Supply, [[Fairey Stooge|Stooge]]. Stooge was more like an armed drone aircraft than a missile. It was flown to a location in front of the target and then cruised toward it until being triggered by the operator. Its low speed and manual guidance meant it was not useful for interceptions outside the immediate area of the ship, and thus did not meet the need for a longer-ranged missile capable of dealing with stand-off weapons. Accordingly, Fairey was ordered to stop work on Stooge in favour of LOPGAP.{{efn-lr|Existing Stooge airframes continued to be test-fired for a time.}} Development was slowed by the [[Air Ministry]] who were opposed to the project as it might take resources away from jet fighter production{{efn-lr|For unclear reasons, considering they were also working on several missile designs of their own.}} and a lack of urgency on the part of both the Admiralty and [[Ministry of Supply]].{{sfn|Grove|2004|p=194}}\n\nA March 1945 report called for the first test launches of LOPGAP from converted [[QF 3.7-inch AA gun|QF 3.7-inch air-aircraft gun]] mounts, the same were also used for Stooge and Brakemine, within two months. They predicted the final system would be about {{convert|19|ft|abbr=on}} long and a twin-launcher would take up about the same room as a twin 5.25-inch gun turret. An April Staff Target called for the system to be able to engage an aircraft flying at {{convert|500|mph|abbr=on}} at altitudes up to {{convert|40,000|ft|abbr=on}} with a maximum weight of {{convert|500|lb|abbr=on}}.{{sfn|Friedman|2012|p=179}}\n\nIn a January 1947 Navy review, the program was given the name Seaslug. This called for a significantly larger weapon than initially envisioned in GAP, capable of single-stage vertical launch, a warhead (and guidance) of {{convert|200|lb|kg|abbr=on}} and an all-up weight of {{convert|1800|lb|kg|abbr=on}}.{{sfn|Twigge|1993|p=28}} Development continued as before but was significantly hampered by the post-war exodus of engineering talent.{{sfn|Harding|2005|p=254}}\n\n===Move to RAE===\nIn 1945 a new Guided Projectiles Establishment was set up under the Controller of Supplies (Air) and in 1946 development of all ongoing missile projects moved to the [[Royal Aircraft Establishment]]'s (RAE) new Controlled Weapons Department, soon to become the Guided Weapons Department.{{sfn|Smith|1965|p=101}} They began considering the beam riding concept in partnership with the [[Telecommunications Research Establishment]] (TRE), the deliberately oddly-named department of the [[Air Ministry]] responsible for [[radar]] development. Over the next year, first Brakemine and then Stooge were moved to the RAE. Seaslug followed in 1947.{{sfn|Smith|1965|p=101}}\n\nDevelopment slowed further, and in July 1947 the Admiralty approached the [[Henry Tizard]] to argue for a more \"virile leadership\" of the program. Tizard called a meeting of the [[Defence Research Policy Committee]] (DRPC) and started a process of pushing through four key missile programs that were intended to enter service in 1957, Seaslug, a corresponding Army/Air Force missile known as [[Red Heathen (missile)|Red Heathen]], the [[Blue Boar (bomb)|Blue Boar]] [[television guidance|television guided]] [[glide bomb]], and the [[Fireflash#Red_Hawk|Red Hawk]] [[air-to-air missile]].{{sfn|Grove|2004|p=194}}\n\nIn March 1948 a new report from the DRPC noted there was not enough manpower for all four projects, and put Seaslug at the bottom of the priority list, claiming air attack would be less likely than submarine in the event of war. They suggested the much longer ranged Red Heathen was more important. The Admiralty was of another opinion on the matter and argued against the change in priority.{{sfn|Grove|2004|p=194}}\n\nThe Navy found an unlikely ally in the Army, who were concerned that Red Heathen was too difficult to move to in a single stage and suggested that Seaslug might be the basis for a more immediate medium-range weapon that could be used both on land and sea. The DPRC also began to have concerns about guiding Red Heathen at its {{convert|100000|yd|km|abbr=on}} maximum range. In September 1948 they agreed to develop Seaslug \"as a matter of insurance\", before further upgrading it in 1949 to \"top priority\".{{sfn|Grove|2004|p=195}} As a result of these changes, the program was seen as having two stages, Stage 1 would deliver missiles in the mid-1950s with roughly {{convert|20|mi}} range with capability mostly against subsonic targets, and a Stage 2 of the early 1960s would have greatly extended range on the order of {{convert|150|mi}} and able to attack supersonic aircraft.\n\n===Experimental systems===\nTwo test systems emerged from this centralization. The CTV.1 was a small unpowered Brakemine-like system devoted to the development of the guidance systems, launched using three [[RP-3]] rocket motors and controlled through the coast phase. A series of CTV designs followed, providing ever-increasing amounts of [[telemetry]] for the guidance and control systems work.{{sfn|Smith|1965|pp=104-105}} GAP became a purely research-oriented system, RTV.1 (rocket test vehicle), as opposed to a prototype missile design, and was used primarily as a platform for testing the rocket motors.{{sfn|Smith|1965|p=105}}{{sfn|Twigge|1993|p=247}} The GAP/RTV.1 efforts would be directed at the Stage 1 design, which would essentially be the Seaslug requirement.\n\nThe relatively small CTV could safely be launched at the Larkhill Range, part of the [[Royal School of Artillery]]. It was equipped with a parachute that allowed it to be recovered. This was not possible for the much longer-ranged RTV, which was fired from [[ParcAberporth|RAF Aberporth]] out over [[Cardigan Bay]] in Wales. The desire to reclaim the RTVs as well led to the opening of a parallel launch facility at the [[RAAF Woomera Range Complex]] and a program that led development of supersonic parachutes.{{sfn|Smith|1965|p=106}}\n\nAs RTV testing continued, the decision was made to build a larger version, RTV.2, which would be more typical of a production missile. During early testing, the design was further modified and renamed GPV, for General Purpose Test Vehicle. Several [[liquid rocket]] motors were tested as part of this program. Early tests demonstrated shifts in the [[center of gravity]] that required active damping, which in turn led to the lengthening of the overall fuselage to become the \"long round\". This version used forward-mounted boosters, which were mounted so their exhaust was just in front of the mid-mounted wings.{{sfn|Smith|1965|p=108}}\n\n===Project 502===\nAs experimental work progressed, the Ministry of Supply began forming an industry team to build production systems. In 1949 this gave rise to the 'Project 502' group from industry, with [[Armstrong Whitworth Aircraft]] and [[Sperry Corporation#British Sperry|Sperry]] in March and [[General Electric Company|GEC]] in September.{{sfn|Twigge|1993|p=28}}\n\nThe 29 July 1949 update of the Staff Target called for a maximum range of {{convert|30000|yd|km|abbr=on}} and a minimum of {{convert|5000|yd|km|abbr=on}}. Maximum altitude should be 55,000&nbsp;ft, but 45,000 would be considered acceptable. A later updated pushed the range to {{convert|30000|-|60000|yd|km|abbr=on}} against a {{convert|600|kn|km/h|abbr=on}}, later {{convert|650|kn|km/h|abbr=on}}, target. It was assumed the targets would \"jink\" at 1G, so the missile needed to maneuver at 4G at sea level and 2.5G at 40,000&nbsp;ft. Additional requirements were the ability to switch between targets in 6 seconds.{{sfn|Friedman|2012|p=179}}\n\nThe designers ultimately selected a maximum range of 30,000&nbsp;yards, which included {{convert|6,000|yd|km|abbr=on}} of coasting after motor burn-out. This was about 50% better than the contemporary US [[RIM-2 Terrier|Terrier]] design. Hit probability was estimated to be 40% at maximum range, so salvos of three missiles would be fired at once, demanding a three-place launcher. This was later reduced back to a twin-launcher when it was realized accessing the missile in the middle launcher was difficult.{{sfn|Friedman|2012|p=179}}\n\n===Changing requirements===\nWhen the deployment of the Seaslug was first being considered, three classes of custom missile-firing ships were considered. The Task Force Ship would be capable of {{convert|30|kn|km/h|abbr=on}} and would tasked with fleet air defence. The Ocean Convoy Escort was a {{convert|17|kn|km/h|abbr=on}} vessel that would provide direct cover over seagoing convoys, while the {{convert|12|kn|km/h|abbr=on}} Coastal Convoy Escort would do the same closer to shore. At that time it was believed that [[aircraft carrier]]s would be able to provide adequate cover over convoys or fleets in the ocean, so attention turned to the Coastal Convoy Escort. Beginning in May 1953 a [[Beachy Head-class repair ship]] was converted into a prototype escort ship, {{HMS|Girdle Ness|}}, to test this fitting.<ref>{{cite book|last=Wise|first=Jon|title=RFA Girdle Ness: Sea Slug Missile Trials Ship|editor=John Jordan|publisher=Conway|location=London|year=2007|series=Warship 2007|pages=9\u201328|isbn=978-1-84486-041-8}}</ref>\n\nFor this role, the densest possible storage was required, so the initial design of a single booster rocket at the base end of the missile, as in most contemporary designs, was abandoned in favour of four smaller boosters wrapped around the fuselage, giving shorter overall length of about {{convert|20|ft|m|abbr=on}} without making the missile larger in diameter as the boosters fitted within the area of the guidance wings. If one of the boosters did not fire the thrust would be significantly off-axis, a possibility which was addressed by moving the boosters forward so their exhaust was near the centre of gravity of the missile, allowing the missile's small control surfaces to remain effective. In contrast, the American Terrier missile was somewhat shorter at {{convert|13|ft|6|in|m|abbr=on}}, but this required an additional tandem booster which took the overall length to {{convert|28|ft|6|in|m|abbr=on}}.{{sfn|Friedman|2012|p=179}}\n\nIn 1954, during another review of the Navy's future operations, consideration turned from a \"hot war\" against the Soviets to a series of \"warm wars\" in the [[third world]]. Among other changes brought about by this review, including the cancellation of a future all-gun cruiser class and ending further conversion of WWII-era destroyers to [[Type 15 frigate]]s, the new environment meant that air cover by carriers could not be guaranteed, and the need for air defence for task-force sized groups became the primary concern. A cut to carrier construction, capping the fleet at four, released funds for missile ship construction. In October 1954, a new design emerged that demanded the speed to keep up with a fleet in combat, have guns limited to self-defence, and carrying a single twin-missile launcher.{{sfn|Friedman|2012|p=181}}\n\nThe designs were continually modified in order to find a suitable arrangement. They started as early as 1953 with a mid-sized cruiser of {{convert|15000|LT|t|abbr=on}} carrying 60 to 90 missiles and a crew of 900. Admiral [[Ralph Edwards (Royal Navy officer)|Ralph Edwards]] pointed out it would be more useful to have a larger number of small ships with 10 to 20 missiles than one larger one, but attempts to design such a ship resulted in one with room for the weapons but not the crew needed to operate them. In May 1955 a wide variety of plans for designs between the two extremes were compared, ranging from 9,850 tons down to 4,550.{{sfn|Friedman|2012|p=182}} After continual comparison and revision, these plans finally gelled around what became the [[County-class destroyer]].{{sfn|Friedman|2012|p=184}}\n\n===Testing===\nTest firings of the GAP-based examples, now known as Rocket Test Vehicle 1, or RTV.1, demonstrated beam riding in October 1956. The Navy had set a date of 1957 for a broad modernization of the fleet, so they desired Seaslug to be cleared for service in 1956. To this end, they accepted the use of liquid fuels in spite of the Navy's concerns with these fuels on ships. However, by 1956 a new [[solid fuel rocket]] had been developed by IMI Summerfield which provided the desired range.{{sfn|Friedman|2012|p=180}}\n\nContinual tests took place over the next four years using both the [[Clausen Rolling Platform]] at [[RAE Aberporth]] and the ''Girdle Ness''. A final series of tests at sea, which culminated in sixteen successful firings, finally cleared the missile for service in 1961.{{sfn|Friedman|2012|p=180}} After more than 250 launches, the Seaslug Mark 1, also known as Guided Weapon System 1, or GWS.1, finally entered service in 1962 on County-class, each fitted with a single twin missile launcher and a complete weapon system with one fire control set and 30 missiles. The Seaslug-armed cruisers were cancelled in 1957.{{sfn|Harding|2005|p=259}}\n\nSeaslug needed height, range and bearing information for targets. By 1955 the Royal Navy considered using the [[Type 984 radar]] on Seaslug-armed cruisers and destroyers to provide this. During development, the projected weight of the radar doubled, to the point where it could still potentially be mounted on cruisers, but was rejected for destroyers because it would have meant sacrificing their 4.5 in gun armament. The gun armament was regarded as essential for the navy's wider role outside the hot war mission. The solution adopted with the first batch of the County-class destroyers was to network them with ships carrying Type 984. The destroyers were given a reduced version of the [[Comprehensive Display System]] (CDS), which was fed by a [[Simplex communication|CDS-link receiver]] called DPD (Digital Picture Transmission or Translation).{{sfn|Harding|2005|p=259}}<ref name=Boslaugh66>{{cite book |title=When Computers Went to Sea: The Digitization of the United States Navy |first1= David L|last1=Boslaugh| page=66| url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=Mi8MhzheOokC&q=Digital+Picture+Transmission+system#v=onepage&q=HMS%20Hermes&f=false|publisher=Matt Loeb|date=1999|isbn=0471472204}}</ref>\n\nThe final set for the County ships, actually more a cruiser type than a destroyer, was quite complex: a [[Type 965]] radar for early warning (P-band, 450 kW peak power, range over 175&nbsp;km), in the County Batch 2 the double antenna AKE-2 had two different frequency settings; a Type 992Q target indicator radar (3&nbsp;GHz, 1.75 MW peak power, 90&nbsp;km range); a Type 278 height finding set (80\u201390&nbsp;km); a Type 901 missile guidance radar (X band, 70&nbsp;km range), that in the Sea Slug Mk 2 had a continuous wave signal (but it was still a beam riding designation radar); a Type 904 fire control radar (used in the MRS-3 system, X-band, 50&nbsp;kW, 35&nbsp;km range) for surface targeting.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.littlewars.org.uk/Seaslug/radar.html|title=Seaslug|publisher=SR Jenkins}}</ref>\n\n==Description==\nThe missile had four wrap-around booster motors that separated after launch. After separation, the main motor ignited to power the missile to the target. The booster motors were positioned at the side of the missile, but this unusual arrangement with the motor nozzles both angled outwards at 22.5\u00b0 and 22.5\u00b0 to the left, the missile entered a gentle roll at launch, evening out differences in the thrusts of the boosters. This meant that large stabilising fins as used on contemporary missiles in service with the [[Royal Air Force]] ([[Bristol Bloodhound]]) and the [[British Army]] ([[English Electric Thunderbird]]) were not required. Once the boosters were jettisoned the control surfaces became active.\n\nGuidance was by radar beam-riding, the beam to be provided by [[Type 901 radar|Type 901 fire-control radar]]. There were four flight modes:\n\n*LOSBR (Line Of Sight, Beam Riding), in which the missile flew up a beam that tracked the target\n*CASWTD (Constant Angle of Sight With Terminal Dive), with the missile climbing at a low angle and then diving onto a low-altitude target at 45\u00b0, used against low flying targets at over 12,000 yards away\n*MICAWBER (Missile In Constant Altitude While BEam Riding), used against low level target approaching at 500\u2013800 feet, it allows switching from CASWTD to LOSBR when the target is closing at the ship\n*Up and over: the standard surface attack mode, using the Type 901 radar slaved to the Type 903 in bearing; the missile is fired at high elevation and then depressed in order to strike the vessel with a steep dive, without arming the fuse.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.littlewars.org.uk/Seaslug/slugmode.html|title=Seaslug|publisher=SR Jenkins}}</ref>\n\nElectrical power when the missile was in flight was provided by a [[flux switching alternator]] with a six tooth rotor.  \"The 1.5 kVA Seaslug generator ran at 24,000 rev/min with a frequency of 2,400 Hz.\"<ref>''Guided Weapons'', by Geoffrey Lee, et al, pub Brassey's, 3rd edition, 1998, {{ISBN|1-85753-152-3}}, p59.</ref>\n\n==Service performance==\nSeaslug was a high-performance weapon in the 1960s, with a single-shot kill probability of 92%, although other sources give lower kill probabilities: 75% for the Mk 1 and 65% for the Mk 2.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.littlewars.org.uk/Seaslug/seaslug03.html|title=Seaslug|publisher=SR Jenkins}}</ref> It was, however, limited by the complicated handling arrangements and since each County class ship carried only a single fire-control radar only one target could be engaged at once, though two missiles could be fired against it.{{citation needed|date=September 2014}}\n\nThe cost of an individual Seaslug missile round in 1961 was approximately \u00a350,000.{{citation needed|date=September 2014}}\n\nDuring the [[Falklands War]] Seaslug was only launched once against an aircraft target, by {{HMS|Antrim|D18|6}}, and did not hit. This is hardly surprising, as the Royal Navy considered the system to be obsolete and the low-level attacks experienced in the Falklands War were outside the missile's operational capacity. It was fired again in anger, this time against an Argentine radar at [[Stanley, Falkland Islands|Stanley]] airfield that the [[Royal Air Force]] had been unable to destroy. During a shore bombardment {{HMS|Glamorgan|D19|6}} triangulated the last known position of the radar with her ESM and fired a Seaslug. She later fired several at the runway to cover it with debris which would have damaged any aircraft attempting to land or take off.  Results, if any, are unknown, but the spectacle of the launch sequence was something of a morale booster to the troops ashore.\n\nSeaslug was withdrawn as the County-class ships were decommissioned. {{HMS|Fife|D20|6}} was converted to a training ship, and had her Seaslug systems removed, freeing up large spaces for classrooms.\n\n==Variants==\n[[File:Sea Slug trials.jpg|thumb|The firing of the first Seaslug test missile from [[HMS Girdle Ness (A387)|HMS ''Girdle Ness'' (A387)]]. This version is based on the RAE's early GPV, and retains the rear-mounted boosters before they moved forward on the \"long round\".]]\nThere were two main variants of the Seaslug:\n\n===Mark 1 (GWS.1)===\nThe Seaslug Mark 1 was powered by the solid-fuel ''Foxhound'' (390&nbsp;kg fuel) sustainer motor{{efn-lr|There is a common error about a liquid-fuel sustainer on this model.}} and ''Gosling''(145&nbsp;kg) booster motors. It had a radio [[proximity fuze]] and {{convert|200|lb|abbr=on}} blast warhead.\n\nThe Mark 1 was a [[beam-riding guidance|beam rider]] missile, meaning the target had to be continually illuminated by the directing radar, so the system was limited to engaging only the number of targets that there were radars to track and lock on.\n\n*Particulars\n**Attack Velocity: {{convert|685|mi/h|km/h|abbr=on}}\n**Range: {{convert|30000|yd|m}}\n**Ceiling: {{convert|55000|ft|m}}\n\n===Mark 2 (GWS.2)===\nThe Seaslug Mark 2 was based on the aborted [[List of Rainbow Codes|Blue Slug]] programme to develop an anti-ship missile using the Seaslug missile and guidance system. The project was cancelled in favour of the [[Green Cheese (missile)|\"Green Cheese\" missile]], a tactical nuclear anti-ship weapon,  but other project developments were incorporated into what became the Mark 2. It had improved low altitude performance and a limited anti-ship capability and entered service in 1971. The Mark 2 utilized an improved [[beam-riding guidance]] system.<!-- {{efn-lr|Another common error is that the Mark-2 has semi-active guidance; actually, it was the same beam-rider than Mark-1 }} --> and solid-state electronics. It was powered by the ''Deerhound'' sustainer motor, with ''Retriever'' boosters. Control was by a modified Type 901M radar and it had an improved infra-red proximity fuze and a [[continuous-rod warhead]] with a smaller, {{convert|56|lb|abbr=on}}, explosive charge (RDX-TNT) and an unfold diameter of about 70 feet (10&nbsp;mm steel rods were used) \n\n*Attack velocity: {{convert|1370|mi/h|km/h|abbr=on}}\n*Range: {{convert|35000|yd|km|abbr=on}}\n*Ceiling: {{convert|65000|ft|m|abbr=on}}\n\nThe capabilities of the new Sea Slug Mk 2, an almost 2.5 ton missile, were much improved compared to the previous Mk 1. The boosters gave a total of about 60 tons-force, with {{convert|186|kg|abbr=on}} fuel for each one (145 kg in the Mk 1), accelerating it to over Mach 2. When they separated because the extreme drag made by the rings all around the missile, the solid fuel sustainer ''Deerhound'' started to burn its {{convert|440|kg|abbr=on}} of propellant (390 kg for the Mk 1) and gave about {{convert|1,820|kg/s|abbr=on}} for 38 seconds. The slender missile remained at over Mach 2-2.5 until the flameout. The missile was made fully controllable about ten seconds after firing, followed by a radio-beacon while it was centered in the radar beam; and armed the proxy fuse (infra-red) at about {{convert|1|km|yd|abbr=on}} from the target, if 'hot', while if 'cold' the missile was detonated by command sent from the ship. \nThe range could be even more than 35,000 yards, especially at high altitude, with head-on supersonic targets. One of the longest shots recorded was made by HMS ''Antrim'' against a target over {{convert|58,000|yd|mi km|abbr=on}} away, with an impact at 34.500 with about 46 seconds flight time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.littlewars.org.uk/Seaslug/firings.html|title=Seaslug firing reports |work=Littlewars|publisher=S R Jenkins |date=27 September 2016}}</ref> The missile was capable to reach potentially aven higher altitude and longer range than nominally assested: even after the engine flameout (over 40 seconds after launch), it retained very high speeds, and one of them even surpassed {{convert|85,000|ft|abbr=on}} before being self-destructed, about one minute after the firing <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.littlewars.org.uk/Seaslug/whoops.html|title=Whoops -A firing that went slightly wrong! |date=6 June 2017 |work=Littlewars |publisher=S R Jenkins}}</ref>\n\nFor both Mark 1 and Mark 2 Sea Slug there were [[drill round]]s (painted blue) for the purpose of training and display rounds (painted red) which could be loaded onto the launcher for port visits and public relations.  \n\n\n===Nuclear variant (not built)===\nIn addition, a [[Nuclear weapon|nuclear-armed]] variant was planned using a low-yield [[Nuclear fission#Fission bombs|fission]] warhead code-named ''Winkle''. ''Winkle'' was never built as it was quickly supplanted by ''Pixie'', a very small [[Nuclear weapon design|unboosted]] warhead with an all-plutonium fissile core [[British nuclear tests at Maralinga|tested]] at [[Maralinga, South Australia|Maralinga]], which was, in turn, replaced by ''Gwen'' \u2014 a British version of\nthe US [[W54]] ''Gnat'' unboosted warhead of approximate yield 1/2 - 2 [[Kiloton]] (kt). The final warhead choice was ''Tony'' - a UK version of the [[W44]] ''[[Tsetse primary|Tsetse]]'' [[Boosted fission weapon|boosted]] warhead, but all nuclear options for Seaslug were subsequently abandoned, and no nuclear-armed variant of Seaslug was ever deployed.\n\n==Operators==\n[[File:Sea Slug operators.png|thumb|400px|Map with Seaslug operators in blue]]\n\n===Royal Navy===\nThe County-class destroyers were specifically built to carry Seaslug and its associated control equipment. The magazine was positioned amidships and missiles were assembled in a central gallery forward of the magazine before being passed to the launcher on the quarterdeck. The handling arrangements were designed with a nuclear-war environment in mind and were therefore entirely under cover.\n\n===Chilean Navy===\nSome of the County-class destroyers were sold to Chile for the [[Chilean Navy]]. The system was decommissioned after the rebuild of the four ships purchased by Chile in the early 1990s.\n\n===Former operators===\n* {{flag|Chile}}: [[Chilean Navy]]\n* {{UK}}: [[Royal Navy]]\n\n==Media appearance==\nA Seaslug system appears in the 1970 ''[[UFO (TV series)|UFO]]'' TV series episode [[Destruction (UFO)|\"Destruction\"]].\n\n==Notes==\n{{Notelist-lr}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|35em}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n* {{cite book\n|title= British Destroyers & Frigates: The Second World War & After\n|first= Norman |last=Friedman\n|publisher= Seaforth Publishing |date=2012\n|ref=harv\n}}\n* {{cite book\n|title=The Royal Navy, 1930-2000: Innovation and Defence\n|editor1-first=Richard \n|editor1-last=Harding \n|isbn=0714657107\n|date= 2005\n|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=bw46M1qI9gM\n|ref=harv\n}}\n* {{cite book\n |title= Fire across the desert: Woomera and the Anglo-Australian Joint Project, 1946-1980\n |date=1989\n |publisher= Australian Govt. Pub. Service\n |first=Peter |last=Morton\n |ref=harv\n}}\n* {{cite journal\n |first=T.L. |last=Smith\n |title=RAE Guided Weapon Test Vehicles in the 1950s\n |journal=The Aeronautical Journal\n |volume=69 |issue=650\n |date=February 1965\n |pages= 101\u2013115\n |doi=10.1017/S000192400006036X\n |ref=harv\n}}\n*{{Cite book\n  |title=The Early Development of Guided Weapons in the United Kingdom, 1940-1960\n  |last=Twigge  |first=Stephen Robert\n  |year=1993\n  |publisher=Taylor & Francis\n  |isbn=3718652978\n  |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=uLqzata5_QQC\n  |ref=harv\n}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* ''Naval Armament'', Doug Richardson, Jane's Publishing, 1981, {{ISBN|0-531-03738-X}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Seaslug (missile)}}\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_ULvSrslNbo Sea Slug Video]\n*[https://www.flightglobal.com/pdfarchive/view/1958/1958-1-%20-%200786.html \"Seaslug - the Most Missile in the Least Space\"] a 1958 ''Flight'' article by [[Bill Gunston]]\n*[http://www.flightglobal.com/pdfarchive/view/1959/1959%20-%200435.html \"Shell for the Seaslug\"] a 1959 article on Seaslug in [[Flight International|''Flight'']] magazine\n*[http://www.flightglobal.com/pdfarchive/view/1962/1962%20-%200142.html \"Seaslug Story\"] a 1962 ''Flight'' article on the Seaslug\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20051109024643/http://www.skomer.u-net.com/projects/seaslug.htm United Kingdom Aerospace and Weapon Projects]\n* [http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/library/report/1984/HJA.htm The Falkland Islands Conflict, 1982: Air Defense Of The Fleet]\n*[http://www.nuclear-weapons.info/vw.htm#Winkle ''Winkle'' - warhead for the planned nuclear variant]\n\n{{UKmissiles}}\n\n[[Category:Cold War surface-to-air missiles of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Naval weapons of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Naval surface-to-air missiles]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox weapon\n|is_missile=yes\n|is_UK=yes\n| image= Sea Slug missile.png\n| image_size = 300\n|caption=Seaslug Mk. II missile\n|name=Seaslug\n|type=surface-to-air missile\n|origin=UK\n|era=Cold War\n|launch_platform=Ship\n|target=Aircraft\n|manufacturer=[[Armstrong Whitworth]]\n|design_date=Mark 1; 1961 <br/>Mark 2; 1965\n|production_date=\n|service=1961 - 1991\n|used_by=UK ([[Royal Navy]]), Chile\n|wars=[[Falklands War]]\n|spec_type=Anti-aircraft\n|diameter=Mk.1; 0.42 m <br/> Mk.2; 0.41 m\n|wingspan=1.44 m\n|length=Mk.1; 6.0 m <br/> Mk.2; 6.1 m\n|weight=Mk.1; 2,080 kg <br/> Mk.2; 2,384 kg\n|speed=Mk.1; {{convert|685|mi/h|km/h|abbr=on}} <br/> Mk.2; {{convert|1370|mi/h|km/h|abbr=on}}\n|vehicle_range=Mk.1; {{convert|30000|yd|m}} <br/> Mk.2; {{convert|35000|yd|m}}\n|ceiling=Mk.1; {{convert|55000|ft|m}} <br/> Mk.2; {{convert|65000|ft|m}}\n|filling=Mk.1; {{convert|200|lb|abbr=on}} blast <br/> Mk.2; [[continuous-rod warhead]]\n|engine=4 solid fuel jettisoned boosters & solid fuel [[sustainer rocket|sustainer]]\n|steering=control surface\n|guidance=[[Beam riding]]\n|variants= Mark 1, Mark 2\n|fuze=Mk.1; Radio proximity & impact<br/>Mk.2; Infra-red proximity\n|number=\n}}\n[[File:Armstrong Whitworth Seaslug missile.jpg|thumb|Seaslug on display at [[Wickenby Aerodrome]], Lincolnshire, UK]]\n'''Seaslug''' was a first-generation [[surface-to-air missile]] designed by [[Armstrong Whitworth]] (later part of the [[Hawker Siddeley]] group) for use by the [[Royal Navy]]. Tracing its history as far back as 1943, it came into operational service in 1961 and was still in use at the time of the [[Falklands War]] in 1982.\n\nSeaslug was intended to engage high-flying targets such as reconnaissance aircraft or bombers before they could launch stand-off weapons. It was only fitted to the Royal Navy's eight [[County-class destroyer]]s which were designed around the missile system.  Later improvements meant that it could also be used against ships. Seaslug was only fired in anger once as an anti-aircraft missile, from {{HMS|Antrim|D18|6}} during the Falklands War, but missed its target. It was also used for surface bombardment.\n\nSeaslug's medium-range role was to be supplanted by a very long-range missile known as [[Blue Envoy]], but this was passed over in favour of a new medium-range system, [[Sea Dart]]. Sea Dart entered service in 1973 on the [[Type 82 destroyer]]s and replaced Seaslug during the 1980s as the {{sclass2-|County|destroyer}}s were removed from service.\n\n==Development==\n===Initial concept===\nIn 1943, the German ''[[Luftwaffe]]'' began the use of [[anti-shipping missile]]s and guided bombs in the Mediterranean Ocean during Allied operations against Italy. These weapons were released outside of [[anti-aircraft gun]] range, which meant that any operations lacking complete [[air superiority]] would be open to attack with little response by the ships.{{sfn|Friedman|2012|p=197}} On 16 March 1944 the first meeting of the \"Guided Anti-Aircraft Projectile Committee\", or GAP Committee, was held.{{sfn|Grove|2004|p=193}}\n\nThe [[Admiralty Signals and Radar Establishment|Admiralty Signals Establishment]] (ASE), in charge of the Navy's [[radar]] development, was working on new radars featuring [[radar lock-on]] that allowed them to accurately track aircraft at long range. This was part of the LRS.1 [[fire-control system]] that allowed large dual-purpose guns to attack bombers at long range.{{sfn|Harding|2005|p=254}} A contemporary [[British Army]] project at Cossors, [[Brakemine]], was working on a system to allow a missile to keep itself centred within a radar beam, a concept known today as [[beam riding]]. The Navy decided to combine the two concepts, using the LRS.1's Type 909 radar with a new missile that differed from Brakemine primarily in requiring longer range and being more robust for shipborne use.{{sfn|Friedman|2012|p=197}}\n\nIn December 1944, GAP put out a Naval Staff Target for a new anti-aircraft weapon,{{sfn|Grove|2004|p=193}} capable of attacking targets at altitudes up to {{convert|50,000|ft|m|abbr=on}} and speeds of up to {{convert|700|mph|abbr=on}}.{{sfn|Grove|2004|p=194}} This project was briefly known as LOPGAP, short for \"Liquid Oxygen and Petrol Guided Anti-aircraft Projectile\",{{sfn|Twigge|1993|p=246}} but soon moved from petrol to [[methanol]] which made the \"LOP\" inaccurate, and the name accordingly changed simply to GAP,{{sfn|Morton|1989|p=209}} and then Seaslug. Efforts{{by whom|date=April 2020}} to change the name to \"Triumph\"{{why|date=April 2020}} failed.{{sfn|Grove|2004|p=194}}\n\n===LOPGAP===\nThe [[Fairey Aviation Company]] was at this time working on a missile project for the Ministry of Supply, [[Fairey Stooge|Stooge]]. Stooge was more like an armed drone aircraft than a missile. It was flown to a location in front of the target and then cruised toward it until being triggered by the operator. Its low speed and manual guidance meant it was not useful for interceptions outside the immediate area of the ship, and thus did not meet the need for a longer-ranged missile capable of dealing with stand-off weapons. Accordingly, Fairey was ordered to stop work on Stooge in favour of LOPGAP.{{efn-lr|Existing Stooge airframes continued to be test-fired for a time.}} Development was slowed by the [[Air Ministry]] who were opposed to the project as it might take resources away from jet fighter production{{efn-lr|For unclear reasons, considering they were also working on several missile designs of their own.}} and a lack of urgency on the part of both the Admiralty and [[Ministry of Supply]].{{sfn|Grove|2004|p=194}}\n\nA March 1945 report called for the first test launches of LOPGAP from converted [[QF 3.7-inch AA gun|QF 3.7-inch air-aircraft gun]] mounts, the same were also used for Stooge and Brakemine, within two months. They predicted the final system would be about {{convert|19|ft|abbr=on}} long and a twin-launcher would take up about the same room as a twin 5.25-inch gun turret. An April Staff Target called for the system to be able to engage an aircraft flying at {{convert|500|mph|abbr=on}} at altitudes up to {{convert|40,000|ft|abbr=on}} with a maximum weight of {{convert|500|lb|abbr=on}}.{{sfn|Friedman|2012|p=179}}\n\nIn a January 1947 Navy review, the program was given the name Seaslug. This called for a significantly larger weapon than initially envisioned in GAP, capable of single-stage vertical launch, a warhead (and guidance) of {{convert|200|lb|kg|abbr=on}} and an all-up weight of {{convert|1800|lb|kg|abbr=on}}.{{sfn|Twigge|1993|p=28}} Development continued as before but was significantly hampered by the post-war exodus of engineering talent.{{sfn|Harding|2005|p=254}}\n\n===Move to RAE===\nIn 1945 a new Guided Projectiles Establishment was set up under the Controller of Supplies (Air) and in 1946 development of all ongoing missile projects moved to the [[Royal Aircraft Establishment]] (RAE) new Controlled Weapons Department, soon to become the Guided Weapons Department.{{sfn|Smith|1965|p=101}} They began considering the beam riding concept in partnership with the [[Telecommunications Research Establishment]] (TRE), the deliberately oddly-named department of the [[Air Ministry]] responsible for [[radar]] development. Over the next year, first Brakemine and then Stooge were moved to the RAE. Seaslug followed in 1947.{{sfn|Smith|1965|p=101}}\n\nDevelopment slowed further, and in July 1947 the Admiralty approached the [[Henry Tizard]] to see a more \"virile leadership\" of the program. Tizard called a meeting of the [[Defence Research Policy Committee]] (DRPC) and started a process of pushing through four key programs that were intended to enter service in 1957, Seaslug, a corresponding Army/Air Force missile known as [[Red Heathen (missile)|Red Heathen]], the [[Blue Boar (bomb)|Blue Boar]] [[television guidance]] [[glide bomb]], and the [[Fireflash#Red_Hawk|Red Hawk]] [[air-to-air missile]].{{sfn|Grove|2004|p=194}}\n\nIn March 1948 a new report from the DRPC noted there was not enough manpower for all four projects, and put Seaslug at the bottom of the priority list, claiming air attack would be less likely than submarine in the event of war. They suggested the much longer ranged Red Heathen was more important. The Admiralty was of another opinion on the matter.{{sfn|Grove|2004|p=194}}\n\nThe Navy found an unlikely ally in the Army, who were concerned that Red Heathen was too difficult to move to in a single stage and suggested that Seaslug might be the basis for a more immediate medium-range weapon that could be used both on land and sea. The DPRC also began to have concerns about guiding Red Heathen at its {{convert|100000|yd|km|abbr=on}} maximum range. In September 1948 they agreed to develop Seaslug \"as a matter of insurance\", before further upgrading it in 1949 to \"top priority\".{{sfn|Grove|2004|p=195}} As a result of these changes, the program was seen as having two stages, Stage 1 would deliver missiles in the mid-1950s with roughly {{convert|20|mi}} range with capability mostly against subsonic targets, and a Stage 2 of the early 1960s would have greatly extended range on the order of {{convert|150|mi}} and able to attack supersonic aircraft.\n\n===Experimental systems===\nTwo test systems emerged from this centralization. The CTV.1 was a small unpowered Brakemine-like system devoted to the development of the guidance systems, launched using three [[RP-3]] rocket motors and controlled through the coast phase. A series of CTV designs followed, providing ever-increasing amounts of [[telemetry]] for the guidance and control systems work.{{sfn|Smith|1965|pp=104-105}} GAP became a purely research-oriented system, RTV.1 (rocket test vehicle), as opposed to a prototype missile design, and was used primarily as a platform for testing the rocket motors.{{sfn|Smith|1965|p=105}}{{sfn|Twigge|1993|p=247}} The GAP/RTV.1 efforts would be directed at the Stage 1 design, which would essentially be the Seaslug requirement.\n\nThe relatively small CTV could safely be launched at the Larkhill Range, part of the [[Royal School of Artillery]]. It was equipped with a parachute that allowed it to be recovered. This was not possible for the much longer-ranged RTV, which was fired from [[ParcAberporth|RAF Aberporth]] out over [[Cardigan Bay]] in Wales. The desire to reclaim the RTVs as well led to the opening of a parallel launch facility at the [[RAAF Woomera Range Complex]] and a program that led development of supersonic parachutes.{{sfn|Smith|1965|p=106}}\n\nAs RTV testing continued, the decision was made to build a larger version, RTV.2, which would be more typical of a production missile. During early testing, the design was further modified and renamed GPV, for General Purpose Test Vehicle. Several [[liquid rocket]] motors were tested as part of this program. Early tests demonstrated shifts in the [[center of gravity]] that required active damping, which in turn led to the lengthening of the overall fuselage to become the \"long round\". This version used forward-mounted boosters, which were mounted so their exhaust was just in front of the mid-mounted wings.{{sfn|Smith|1965|p=108}}\n\n===Project 502===\nAs experimental work progressed, the Ministry of Supply began forming an industry team to build production systems. In 1949 this gave rise to the 'Project 502' group from industry, with [[Armstrong Whitworth Aircraft]] and [[Sperry Corporation#British Sperry|Sperry]] in March and [[General Electric Company|GEC]] in September.{{sfn|Twigge|1993|p=28}}\n\nThe 29 July 1949 update of the Staff Target called for a maximum range of {{convert|30000|yd|km|abbr=on}} and a minimum of {{convert|5000|yd|km|abbr=on}}. Maximum altitude should be 55,000&nbsp;ft, but 45,000 would be considered acceptable. A later updated pushed the range to {{convert|30000|-|60000|yd|km|abbr=on}} against a {{convert|600|kn|km/h|abbr=on}}, later {{convert|650|kn|km/h|abbr=on}}, target. It was assumed the targets would \"jink\" at 1G, so the missile needed to maneuver at 4G at sea level and 2.5G at 40,000&nbsp;ft. Additional requirements were the ability to switch between targets in 6 seconds.{{sfn|Friedman|2012|p=179}}\n\nThe designers ultimately selected a maximum range of 30,000&nbsp;yards, which included {{convert|6,000|yd|km|abbr=on}} of coasting after motor burn-out. This was about 50% better than the contemporary US [[RIM-2 Terrier|Terrier]] design. Hit probability was estimated to be 40% at maximum range, so salvos of three missiles would be fired at once, demanding a three-place launcher. This was later reduced back to a twin-launcher when it was realized accessing the missile in the middle launcher was difficult.{{sfn|Friedman|2012|p=179}}\n\n===Changing requirements===\nWhen the deployment of the Seaslug was first being considered, three classes of custom missile-firing ships were considered. The Task Force Ship would be capable of {{convert|30|kn|km/h|abbr=on}} and would tasked with fleet air defence. The Ocean Convoy Escort was a {{convert|17|kn|km/h|abbr=on}} vessel that would provide direct cover over seagoing convoys, while the {{convert|12|kn|km/h|abbr=on}} Coastal Convoy Escort would do the same closer to shore. At that time it was believed that [[aircraft carrier]]s would be able to provide adequate cover over convoys or fleets in the ocean, so attention turned to the Coastal Convoy Escort. Beginning in May 1953 a [[Beachy Head-class repair ship]] was converted into a prototype escort ship, {{HMS|Girdle Ness|}}, to test this fitting.<ref>{{cite book|last=Wise|first=Jon|title=RFA Girdle Ness: Sea Slug Missile Trials Ship|editor=John Jordan|publisher=Conway|location=London|year=2007|series=Warship 2007|pages=9\u201328|isbn=978-1-84486-041-8}}</ref>\n\nFor this role, the densest possible storage was required, so the initial design of a single booster rocket at the base end of the missile, as in most contemporary designs, was abandoned in favour of four smaller boosters wrapped around the fuselage, giving shorter overall length of about {{convert|20|ft|m|abbr=on}} without making the missile larger in diameter as the boosters fitted within the area of the guidance wings. If one of the boosters did not fire the thrust would be significantly off-axis, a possibility which was addressed by moving the boosters forward so their exhaust was near the centre of gravity of the missile, allowing the missile's small control surfaces to remain effective. In contrast, the American Terrier missile was somewhat shorter at {{convert|13|ft|6|in|m|abbr=on}}, but this required an additional tandem booster which took the overall length to {{convert|28|ft|6|in|m|abbr=on}}.{{sfn|Friedman|2012|p=179}}\n\nIn 1954, during another review of the Navy's future operations, consideration turned from a \"hot war\" against the Soviets to a series of \"warm wars\" in the [[third world]]. Among other changes brought about by this review, including the cancellation of a future all-gun cruiser class and ending further conversion of WWII-era destroyers to [[Type 15 frigate]]s, the new environment meant that air cover by carriers could not be guaranteed, and the need for air defence for task-force sized groups became the primary concern. A cut to carrier construction, capping the fleet at four, released funds for missile ship construction. In October 1954, a new design emerged that demanded the speed to keep up with a fleet in combat, have guns limited to self-defence, and carrying a single twin-missile launcher.{{sfn|Friedman|2012|p=181}}\n\nThe designs were continually modified in order to find a suitable arrangement. They started as early as 1953 with a mid-sized cruiser of {{convert|15000|LT|t|abbr=on}} carrying 60 to 90 missiles and a crew of 900. Admiral [[Ralph Edwards (Royal Navy officer)|Ralph Edwards]] pointed out it would be more useful to have a larger number of small ships with 10 to 20 missiles than one larger one, but attempts to design such a ship resulted in one with room for the weapons but not the crew needed to operate them. In May 1955 a wide variety of plans for designs between the two extremes were compared, ranging from 9,850 tons down to 4,550.{{sfn|Friedman|2012|p=182}} After continual comparison and revision, these plans finally gelled around what became the [[County-class destroyer]].{{sfn|Friedman|2012|p=184}}\n\n===Testing===\nTest firings of the GAP-based examples, now known as Rocket Test Vehicle 1, or RTV.1, demonstrated beam riding in October 1956. The Navy had set a date of 1957 for a broad modernization of the fleet, so they desired Seaslug to be cleared for service in 1956. To this end, they accepted the use of liquid fuels in spite of the Navy's concerns with these fuels on ships. However, by 1956 a new [[solid fuel rocket]] had been developed by IMI Summerfield which provided the desired range.{{sfn|Friedman|2012|p=180}}\n\nContinual tests took place over the next four years using both the [[Clausen Rolling Platform]] at [[RAE Aberporth]] and the ''Girdle Ness''. A final series of tests at sea, which culminated in sixteen successful firings, finally cleared the missile for service in 1961.{{sfn|Friedman|2012|p=180}} After more than 250 launches, the Seaslug Mark 1, also known as Guided Weapon System 1, or GWS.1, finally entered service in 1962 on County-class, each fitted with a single twin missile launcher and a complete weapon system with one fire control set and 30 missiles. The Seaslug-armed cruisers were cancelled in 1957.{{sfn|Harding|2005|p=259}}\n\nSeaslug needed height, range and bearing information for targets. By 1955 the Royal Navy considered using the [[Type 984 radar]] on Seaslug-armed cruisers and destroyers to provide this. During development, the projected weight of the radar doubled, to the point where it could still potentially be mounted on cruisers, but was rejected for destroyers because it would have meant sacrificing their 4.5 in gun armament. The gun armament was regarded as essential for the navy's wider role outside the hot war mission. The solution adopted with the first batch of the County-class destroyers was to network them with ships carrying Type 984. The destroyers were given a reduced version of the [[Comprehensive Display System]] (CDS), which was fed by a [[Simplex communication|CDS-link receiver]] called DPD (Digital Picture Transmission or Translation).{{sfn|Harding|2005|p=259}}<ref name=Boslaugh66>{{cite book |title=When Computers Went to Sea: The Digitization of the United States Navy |first1= David L|last1=Boslaugh| page=66| url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=Mi8MhzheOokC&q=Digital+Picture+Transmission+system#v=onepage&q=HMS%20Hermes&f=false|publisher=Matt Loeb|date=1999|isbn=0471472204}}</ref>\n\nThe final set for the County ships, actually more a cruiser type than a destroyer, was quite complex: a [[Type 965]] radar for early warning (P-band, 450 kW peak power, range over 175&nbsp;km), in the County Batch 2 the double antenna AKE-2 had two different frequency settings; a Type 992Q target indicator radar (3&nbsp;GHz, 1.75 MW peak power, 90&nbsp;km range); a Type 278 height finding set (80\u201390&nbsp;km); a Type 901 missile guidance radar (X band, 70&nbsp;km range), that in the Sea Slug Mk 2 had a continuous wave signal (but it was still a beam riding designation radar); a Type 904 fire control radar (used in the MRS-3 system, X-band, 50&nbsp;kW, 35&nbsp;km range) for surface targeting.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.littlewars.org.uk/Seaslug/radar.html|title=Seaslug|publisher=SR Jenkins}}</ref>\n\n==Description==\nThe missile had four wrap-around booster motors that separated after launch. After separation, the main motor ignited to power the missile to the target. The booster motors were positioned at the side of the missile, but this unusual arrangement with the motor nozzles both angled outwards at 22.5\u00b0 and 22.5\u00b0 to the left, the missile entered a gentle roll at launch, evening out differences in the thrusts of the boosters. This meant that large stabilising fins as used on contemporary missiles in service with the [[Royal Air Force]] ([[Bristol Bloodhound]]) and the [[British Army]] ([[English Electric Thunderbird]]) were not required. Once the boosters were jettisoned the control surfaces became active.\n\nGuidance was by radar beam-riding, the beam to be provided by [[Type 901 radar|Type 901 fire-control radar]]. There were four flight modes:\n\n*LOSBR (Line Of Sight, Beam Riding), in which the missile flew up a beam that tracked the target\n*CASWTD (Constant Angle of Sight With Terminal Dive), with the missile climbing at a low angle and then diving onto a low-altitude target at 45\u00b0, used against low flying targets at over 12,000 yards away\n*MICAWBER (Missile In Constant Altitude While BEam Riding), used against low level target approaching at 500\u2013800 feet, it allows switching from CASWTD to LOSBR when the target is closing at the ship\n*Up and over: the standard surface attack mode, using the Type 901 radar slaved to the Type 903 in bearing; the missile is fired at high elevation and then depressed in order to strike the vessel with a steep dive, without arming the fuse.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.littlewars.org.uk/Seaslug/slugmode.html|title=Seaslug|publisher=SR Jenkins}}</ref>\n\nElectrical power when the missile was in flight was provided by a [[flux switching alternator]] with a six tooth rotor.  \"The 1.5 kVA Seaslug generator ran at 24,000 rev/min with a frequency of 2,400 Hz.\"<ref>''Guided Weapons'', by Geoffrey Lee, et al, pub Brassey's, 3rd edition, 1998, {{ISBN|1-85753-152-3}}, p59.</ref>\n\n==Service performance==\nSeaslug was a high-performance weapon in the 1960s, with a single-shot kill probability of 92%, although other sources give lower kill probabilities: 75% for the Mk 1 and 65% for the Mk 2.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.littlewars.org.uk/Seaslug/seaslug03.html|title=Seaslug|publisher=SR Jenkins}}</ref> It was, however, limited by the complicated handling arrangements and since each County class ship carried only a single fire-control radar only one target could be engaged at once, though two missiles could be fired against it.{{citation needed|date=September 2014}}\n\nThe cost of an individual Seaslug missile round in 1961 was approximately \u00a350,000.{{citation needed|date=September 2014}}\n\nDuring the [[Falklands War]] Seaslug was only launched once against an aircraft target, by {{HMS|Antrim|D18|6}}, and did not hit. This is hardly surprising, as the Royal Navy considered the system to be obsolete and the low-level attacks experienced in the Falklands War were outside the missile's operational capacity. It was fired again in anger, this time against an Argentine radar at [[Stanley, Falkland Islands|Stanley]] airfield that the [[Royal Air Force]] had been unable to destroy. During a shore bombardment {{HMS|Glamorgan|D19|6}} triangulated the last known position of the radar with her ESM and fired a Seaslug. She later fired several at the runway to cover it with debris which would have damaged any aircraft attempting to land or take off.  Results, if any, are unknown, but the spectacle of the launch sequence was something of a morale booster to the troops ashore.\n\nSeaslug was withdrawn as the County-class ships were decommissioned. {{HMS|Fife|D20|6}} was converted to a training ship, and had her Seaslug systems removed, freeing up large spaces for classrooms.\n\n==Variants==\n[[File:Sea Slug trials.jpg|thumb|The firing of the first Seaslug test missile from [[HMS Girdle Ness (A387)|HMS ''Girdle Ness'' (A387)]]. This version is based on the RAE's early GPV, and retains the rear-mounted boosters before they moved forward on the \"long round\".]]\nThere were two main variants of the Seaslug:\n\n===Mark 1 (GWS.1)===\nThe Seaslug Mark 1 was powered by the solid-fuel ''Foxhound'' (390&nbsp;kg fuel) sustainer motor{{efn-lr|There is a common error about a liquid-fuel sustainer on this model.}} and ''Gosling''(145&nbsp;kg) booster motors. It had a radio [[proximity fuze]] and {{convert|200|lb|abbr=on}} blast warhead.\n\nThe Mark 1 was a [[beam-riding guidance|beam rider]] missile, meaning the target had to be continually illuminated by the directing radar, so the system was limited to engaging only the number of targets that there were radars to track and lock on.\n\n*Particulars\n**Attack Velocity: {{convert|685|mi/h|km/h|abbr=on}}\n**Range: {{convert|30000|yd|m}}\n**Ceiling: {{convert|55000|ft|m}}\n\n===Mark 2 (GWS.2)===\nThe Seaslug Mark 2 was based on the aborted [[List of Rainbow Codes|Blue Slug]] programme to develop an anti-ship missile using the Seaslug missile and guidance system. The project was cancelled in favour of the [[Green Cheese (missile)|\"Green Cheese\" missile]], a tactical nuclear anti-ship weapon,  but other project developments were incorporated into what became the Mark 2. It had improved low altitude performance and a limited anti-ship capability and entered service in 1971. The Mark 2 utilized an improved [[beam-riding guidance]] system.<!-- {{efn-lr|Another common error is that the Mark-2 has semi-active guidance; actually, it was the same beam-rider than Mark-1 }} --> and solid-state electronics. It was powered by the ''Deerhound'' sustainer motor, with ''Retriever'' boosters. Control was by a modified Type 901M radar and it had an improved infra-red proximity fuze and a [[continuous-rod warhead]] with a smaller, {{convert|56|lb|abbr=on}}, explosive charge (RDX-TNT) and an unfold diameter of about 70 feet (10&nbsp;mm steel rods were used) \n\n*Attack velocity: {{convert|1370|mi/h|km/h|abbr=on}}\n*Range: {{convert|35000|yd|km|abbr=on}}\n*Ceiling: {{convert|65000|ft|m|abbr=on}}\n\nThe capabilities of the new Sea Slug Mk 2, an almost 2.5 ton missile, were much improved compared to the previous Mk 1. The boosters gave a total of about 60 tons-force, with {{convert|186|kg|abbr=on}} fuel for each one (145 kg in the Mk 1), accelerating it to over Mach 2. When they separated because the extreme drag made by the rings all around the missile, the solid fuel sustainer ''Deerhound'' started to burn its {{convert|440|kg|abbr=on}} of propellant (390 kg for the Mk 1) and gave about {{convert|1,820|kg/s|abbr=on}} for 38 seconds. The slender missile remained at over Mach 2-2.5 until the flameout. The missile was made fully controllable about ten seconds after firing, followed by a radio-beacon while it was centered in the radar beam; and armed the proxy fuse (infra-red) at about {{convert|1|km|yd|abbr=on}} from the target, if 'hot', while if 'cold' the missile was detonated by command sent from the ship. \nThe range could be even more than 35,000 yards, especially at high altitude, with head-on supersonic targets. One of the longest shots recorded was made by HMS ''Antrim'' against a target over {{convert|58,000|yd|mi km|abbr=on}} away, with an impact at 34.500 with about 46 seconds flight time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.littlewars.org.uk/Seaslug/firings.html|title=Seaslug firing reports |work=Littlewars|publisher=S R Jenkins |date=27 September 2016}}</ref> The missile was capable to reach potentially aven higher altitude and longer range than nominally assested: even after the engine flameout (over 40 seconds after launch), it retained very high speeds, and one of them even surpassed {{convert|85,000|ft|abbr=on}} before being self-destructed, about one minute after the firing <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.littlewars.org.uk/Seaslug/whoops.html|title=Whoops -A firing that went slightly wrong! |date=6 June 2017 |work=Littlewars |publisher=S R Jenkins}}</ref>\n\nFor both Mark 1 and Mark 2 Sea Slug there were [[drill round]]s (painted blue) for the purpose of training and display rounds (painted red) which could be loaded onto the launcher for port visits and public relations.  \n\n\n===Nuclear variant (not built)===\nIn addition, a [[Nuclear weapon|nuclear-armed]] variant was planned using a low-yield [[Nuclear fission#Fission bombs|fission]] warhead code-named ''Winkle''. ''Winkle'' was never built as it was quickly supplanted by ''Pixie'', a very small [[Nuclear weapon design|unboosted]] warhead with an all-plutonium fissile core [[British nuclear tests at Maralinga|tested]] at [[Maralinga, South Australia|Maralinga]], which was, in turn, replaced by ''Gwen'' \u2014 a British version of\nthe US [[W54]] ''Gnat'' unboosted warhead of approximate yield 1/2 - 2 [[Kiloton]] (kt). The final warhead choice was ''Tony'' - a UK version of the [[W44]] ''[[Tsetse primary|Tsetse]]'' [[Boosted fission weapon|boosted]] warhead, but all nuclear options for Seaslug were subsequently abandoned, and no nuclear-armed variant of Seaslug was ever deployed.\n\n==Operators==\n[[File:Sea Slug operators.png|thumb|400px|Map with Seaslug operators in blue]]\n\n===Royal Navy===\nThe County-class destroyers were specifically built to carry Seaslug and its associated control equipment. The magazine was positioned amidships and missiles were assembled in a central gallery forward of the magazine before being passed to the launcher on the quarterdeck. The handling arrangements were designed with a nuclear-war environment in mind and were therefore entirely under cover.\n\n===Chilean Navy===\nSome of the County-class destroyers were sold to Chile for the [[Chilean Navy]]. The system was decommissioned after the rebuild of the four ships purchased by Chile in the early 1990s.\n\n===Former operators===\n* {{flag|Chile}}: [[Chilean Navy]]\n* {{UK}}: [[Royal Navy]]\n\n==Media appearance==\nA Seaslug system appears in the 1970 ''[[UFO (TV series)|UFO]]'' TV series episode [[Destruction (UFO)|\"Destruction\"]].\n\n==Notes==\n{{Notelist-lr}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|35em}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n* {{cite book\n|title= British Destroyers & Frigates: The Second World War & After\n|first= Norman |last=Friedman\n|publisher= Seaforth Publishing |date=2012\n|ref=harv\n}}\n* {{cite book\n|title=The Royal Navy, 1930-2000: Innovation and Defence\n|editor1-first=Richard \n|editor1-last=Harding \n|isbn=0714657107\n|date= 2005\n|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=bw46M1qI9gM\n|ref=harv\n}}\n* {{cite book\n |title= Fire across the desert: Woomera and the Anglo-Australian Joint Project, 1946-1980\n |date=1989\n |publisher= Australian Govt. Pub. Service\n |first=Peter |last=Morton\n |ref=harv\n}}\n* {{cite journal\n |first=T.L. |last=Smith\n |title=RAE Guided Weapon Test Vehicles in the 1950s\n |journal=The Aeronautical Journal\n |volume=69 |issue=650\n |date=February 1965\n |pages= 101\u2013115\n |doi=10.1017/S000192400006036X\n |ref=harv\n}}\n*{{Cite book\n  |title=The Early Development of Guided Weapons in the United Kingdom, 1940-1960\n  |last=Twigge  |first=Stephen Robert\n  |year=1993\n  |publisher=Taylor & Francis\n  |isbn=3718652978\n  |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=uLqzata5_QQC\n  |ref=harv\n}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* ''Naval Armament'', Doug Richardson, Jane's Publishing, 1981, {{ISBN|0-531-03738-X}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Seaslug (missile)}}\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_ULvSrslNbo Sea Slug Video]\n*[https://www.flightglobal.com/pdfarchive/view/1958/1958-1-%20-%200786.html \"Seaslug - the Most Missile in the Least Space\"] a 1958 ''Flight'' article by [[Bill Gunston]]\n*[http://www.flightglobal.com/pdfarchive/view/1959/1959%20-%200435.html \"Shell for the Seaslug\"] a 1959 article on Seaslug in [[Flight International|''Flight'']] magazine\n*[http://www.flightglobal.com/pdfarchive/view/1962/1962%20-%200142.html \"Seaslug Story\"] a 1962 ''Flight'' article on the Seaslug\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20051109024643/http://www.skomer.u-net.com/projects/seaslug.htm United Kingdom Aerospace and Weapon Projects]\n* [http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/library/report/1984/HJA.htm The Falkland Islands Conflict, 1982: Air Defense Of The Fleet]\n*[http://www.nuclear-weapons.info/vw.htm#Winkle ''Winkle'' - warhead for the planned nuclear variant]\n\n{{UKmissiles}}\n\n[[Category:Cold War surface-to-air missiles of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Naval weapons of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Naval surface-to-air missiles]]\n", "name_user": "Maury Markowitz", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eMove to RAE", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Seaslug_(missile)"}
{"title_page": "Saddar", "text_new": "{{Use Pakistani English|date=February 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2018}}{{about||the wider borough|Saddar Town}}{{Infobox settlement\n<!-- Basic info  ---------------->| name                            = Saddar<br> {{nq|\u0635\u062f\u0631}}\n| established_date                = 1839\n<!-- Population   ----------------------->| leader_name                     = \n| leader_title1                   = \n| leader_name1                    = \n| leader_title2                   = \n| leader_name2                    = \n| established_title               = Established\n| population_as_of                = \n| government_type                 = Town Council\n| population_footnotes            = \n| population_note                 = \n| population_total                = <!-- General information  --------------->\n\n<!-- Area/postal codes & others -------->| postal_code_type                = <!-- enter ZIP code, Postcode, Post code, Postal code... -->\n| postal_code                     = \n| area_code                       = \n| website                         = \n| leader_title                    = \n| government_footnotes            = \n| settlement_type                 = [[Locality (settlement)|Locality]]\n<!-- images and maps  ----------->| subdivision_type                = Country\n| image_skyline                   = File:PK Karachi asv2020-02 img37 Empress Market.jpg\n| image_caption                   = [[Empress Market]]\n| image_flag                      = \n| image_seal                      = \n| image_map                       = KarachiSaddar.png\n| map_caption                     = <!-- Location ------------------>\nStreet map from [[OpenStreetMap]]\n| subdivision_name                = [[Pakistan]]\n| p1                              = Bohri Bazaar, Preedy Quarters\n| subdivision_type1               = Province\n| subdivision_name1               = [[Sindh]]\n| subdivision_type2               = City District\n| subdivision_name2               = [[Karachi]]\n| leader_title1                   = Constituency\n| leader_name1                    = [[NA-247 (Karachi South-II)]]\n| leader_title2                   = National Assembly Member\n| leader_name2                    = [[Aftab Siddiqui]] ([[Pakistan Tehreek-e-Insaf|PTI]])\n| parts_type                      = \n| parts_style                     = coll,para\n| parts                           = \n| official_name                   = \n}}\n'''Saddar''' ({{lang-ur|{{nq|\u0635\u062f\u0631}}}}), also known as '''Saddar Bazaar''', is a neighbourhood in [[Karachi]], [[Pakistan]].<ref>[http://www.karachicity.gov.pk/town/index.asp?txtTown=Saddar Saddar Town \u2013 Government of Karachi] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060613010729/http://karachicity.gov.pk/town/index.asp?txtTown=Saddar |date=2006-06-13 }}</ref> The locality was developed as the primary commercial district during the period of British-era rule in Karachi. As a result, Saddar contains a large concentration of colonial-era architecture.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thepeninsulaqatar.com/article/01/03/2018/Pakistan-s-crumbling-architectural-heritage|title=Pakistan's crumbling architectural heritage - The Peninsula Qatar|website=www.thepeninsulaqatar.com|access-date=2018-03-09}}</ref> \n\n==History==\n[[File:Empressmkt1890.jpg|thumb|[[Empress Market]] in 1890]]\nSaddar was established by the British in 1839 as a commercial district for Karachi's European population,<ref>{{Cite book|last=Lari|first=Yasmeen|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wQ5uAAAAMAAJ&q=saddar+1839&dq=saddar+1839&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjMtbuxg8noAhULsJ4KHa3XCGAQ6AEwA3oECAUQAg|title=The Dual City: Karachi During the Raj|last2=Lari|first2=Mihail S.|date=1996|publisher=Heritage Foundation|isbn=978-0-19-577735-2|language=en}}</ref> to the east of the bazaars of old Karachi in [[Mithadar]], [[Kharadar]], and Jodia Bazaar which served the native population. Following the annexation of [[Sindh]] in 1843, Saddar became the location of administrative and military functions. Following the [[Mutiny of 1857]], rebels were executed at by being blown from the mouths of cannons at Saddar's military parade grounds.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=Haider|first=Azimusshan|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xA0rAAAAMAAJ&q=karachi+empress+market+1857&dq=karachi+empress+market+1857&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiapN_hhMnoAhW-HDQIHbr2BS8Q6AEwAXoECAAQAg|title=History of Karachi: With Special Reference to Educational, Demographical, and Commercial Developments, 1839-1900|date=1974|publisher=Haider|language=en}}</ref>\n\nKarachi's most elite Catholic institutions were quickly established in Karachi: St Patrick\u2019s High School and St Joseph\u2019s Convent High School, wereset up in 1861 and 1862 respectively.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://arifhasan.org/culture/karachi-ch/the-future-of-karachis-saddar|title=The Future Of Karachi\u2019s Saddar|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> The [[Edulji Dinshaw Dispensary]] was established in 1882. The \"McKenzie Pavilion Grounds\", now known as Jehangir Park, was established in 1883.<ref name=\":1\" /> [[Empress Market]] was established at the site of the execution grounds in 1889,<ref name=\":0\" /> and was originally meant to serve British administrators, soldiers, and their families. The area around the market saw the establishment of posh bars, cafes, and restaurants, such as the Saddar Tea Rooms, Elphinstone Restaurant, the old Todi shop and Caf\u00e9 Parisian.<ref name=\":1\" /> A dress-code was enforced in the posh Saddar area, leading it to be eventually known as the \"European Quarter\" of Karachi.<ref name=\":1\" />\nFollowing independence in 1947, Saddar remained a centre of multi-class interaction. Bars, clubs, and business catering to different social classes co-existed in the area.<ref name=\":1\" /> Several institutions of higher learning were within walking distance, including [[D. J. Sindh Government Science College]], and [[Sindh Muslim Law College]], and Regal Bazar became home to a weekly book market that still takes place.<ref name=\":1\" /> Saddar was also within easy walking distance from government institutions to the east of Saddar, and [[Civil Lines, Karachi|Civil Lines]] to the south. The most important churches in Karachi are located in Saddar, as well as Karachi's biggest Parsi fire temple. \n\nFollowing the abolishment of alcohol by [[Zulfikar Ali Bhutto]] in the early 1970s in an attempt to appease conservative forces, Saddar's nightlife scene was decimated.<ref name=\":1\" /> In 1977, dictator [[Muhammad Zia-ul-Haq]] instituted an Islamization agenda that was opposed by the city's wealthy and westernized elite. These classes withdrew from much of public life in Saddar, and instead established exclusive social clubs in Karachi's wealthy residential districts. As a result, Saddar's commercial markets began to serve only lower and lower-middle classes.<ref name=\":1\" /> The area remained a large commuter hub, and so hawker stalls began encroaching on sidewalks in order to cater to the growing number of commuters.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nA large multiplex cinema was established in the early 2000s, leading to a small wave of gentrification in the area. In 2019, in an effort to \"clean up\" the Empress Market, all stalls outside of the market which had been established in the plaza around the market were demolished in a controversial move.<ref name=\":1\" /> \n\n==Gallery ==\nThe following are heritage buildings in Saddar which are protected by the [[Government of Sindh]]:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://antiquities.sindhculture.gov.pk/index.php/publication/reports/111-karachi-heritage-building-re-survey-project/308-saddar-bazaar-quarter-february-2008|title=SADDAR BAZAAR QUARTER FEBRUARY 2008|website=antiquities.sindhculture.gov.pk|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref><gallery>\nFile:Mohammad Ali Building.jpg|The ''Mohamedali'' building is located on [[Zaibunnisa Street]].\nFile:Katchi Memon Masjid 02.jpg|The [[Kutchi Memon]] Mosque was built in Saddar, and is a major centre for Memons in the city.\nFile:St. Andrews church.jpg|[[St Andrew's Church, Karachi|St. Andrew's Church]] in Saddar was built in 1868.\nFile:Ilaco House Photo by Aliraza Khatri.jpg|Ilaco House on the corner of Dundass and [[Zaibunnisa Street|Zaibunnisa Streets]]\nFile:Khyber Hotel on a busy street.JPG|The colonial-era Khyber Hotel\nFile:Edulji Dinshaw Dispensary 01.jpg|[[Edulji Dinshaw Dispensary]], built in 1882\nFile:PK Karachi asv2020-02 img36 Empress Market.jpg|[[Empress Market]], built in 1889\nFile:When art meets religion.jpg|Qasaban Mosque\nFile:Farid Mansion.jpg|Farid Mansion, on Raja Ghaznafar Ali Street (Somerset Street)\nFile:PK Karachi asv2020-02 img40 StPatrick Cathedral (retouched).jpg|Saddar's [[Saint Patrick's Cathedral, Karachi|St. Patrick's Cathedral]] is seat of the [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Karachi]].\n</gallery>\n\n\n==See also==\n*[[Sindh Baloch Cooperative Housing Society]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.karachicity.gov.pk/ Karachi Website]\n\n{{Neighbourhoods of Karachi}}\n\n<br />\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Saddar}}\n[[Category:Neighbourhoods of Karachi]]\n[[Category:Central business districts in Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Saddar Town]]\n\n{{Karachi-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use Pakistani English|date=February 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2018}}{{about||the wider borough|Saddar Town}}{{Infobox settlement\n<!-- Basic info  ---------------->| name                            = Saddar<br> {{nq|\u0635\u062f\u0631}}\n| established_date                = 1839\n<!-- Population   ----------------------->| leader_name                     = \n| leader_title1                   = \n| leader_name1                    = \n| leader_title2                   = \n| leader_name2                    = \n| established_title               = Established\n| population_as_of                = \n| government_type                 = Town Council\n| population_footnotes            = \n| population_note                 = \n| population_total                = <!-- General information  --------------->\n\n<!-- Area/postal codes & others -------->| postal_code_type                = <!-- enter ZIP code, Postcode, Post code, Postal code... -->\n| postal_code                     = \n| area_code                       = \n| website                         = \n| leader_title                    = \n| government_footnotes            = \n| settlement_type                 = [[Locality (settlement)|Locality]]\n<!-- images and maps  ----------->| subdivision_type                = Country\n| image_skyline                   = File:PK Karachi asv2020-02 img37 Empress Market.jpg\n| image_caption                   = [[Empress Market]]\n| image_flag                      = \n| image_seal                      = \n| image_map                       = KarachiSaddar.png\n| map_caption                     = <!-- Location ------------------>\nStreet map from [[OpenStreetMap]]\n| subdivision_name                = [[Pakistan]]\n| p1                              = Bohri Bazaar, Preedy Quarters\n| subdivision_type1               = Province\n| subdivision_name1               = [[Sindh]]\n| subdivision_type2               = City District\n| subdivision_name2               = [[Karachi]]\n| leader_title1                   = Constituency\n| leader_name1                    = [[NA-247 (Karachi South-II)]]\n| leader_title2                   = National Assembly Member\n| leader_name2                    = [[Aftab Siddiqui]] ([[Pakistan Tehreek-e-Insaf|PTI]])\n| parts_type                      = \n| parts_style                     = coll,para\n| parts                           = \n| official_name                   = \n}}\n'''Saddar''' ({{lang-ur|{{nq|\u0635\u062f\u0631}}}}), also known as '''Saddar Bazaar''', is a neighbourhood in [[Karachi]], [[Pakistan]].<ref>[http://www.karachicity.gov.pk/town/index.asp?txtTown=Saddar Saddar Town \u2013 Government of Karachi] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060613010729/http://karachicity.gov.pk/town/index.asp?txtTown=Saddar |date=2006-06-13 }}</ref> The locality was developed as the primary commercial district during the period of British-era rule in Karachi. As a result, Saddar contains a large concentration of colonial-era architecture.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thepeninsulaqatar.com/article/01/03/2018/Pakistan-s-crumbling-architectural-heritage|title=Pakistan's crumbling architectural heritage - The Peninsula Qatar|website=www.thepeninsulaqatar.com|access-date=2018-03-09}}</ref> \n\n==History==\n[[File:Empressmkt1890.jpg|thumb|[[Empress Market]] in 1890]]\nSaddar was established by the British in 1839 as a commercial district for Karachi's European population,<ref>{{Cite book|last=Lari|first=Yasmeen|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wQ5uAAAAMAAJ&q=saddar+1839&dq=saddar+1839&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjMtbuxg8noAhULsJ4KHa3XCGAQ6AEwA3oECAUQAg|title=The Dual City: Karachi During the Raj|last2=Lari|first2=Mihail S.|date=1996|publisher=Heritage Foundation|isbn=978-0-19-577735-2|language=en}}</ref> to the east of the bazaars of old Karachi in [[Mithadar]], [[Kharadar]], and Jodia Bazaar which served the native population. Following the annexation of [[Sindh]] in 1843, Saddar became the location of administrative and military functions. Following the [[Mutiny of 1857]], rebels were executed at by being blown from the mouths of cannons at Saddar's military parade grounds.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=Haider|first=Azimusshan|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xA0rAAAAMAAJ&q=karachi+empress+market+1857&dq=karachi+empress+market+1857&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiapN_hhMnoAhW-HDQIHbr2BS8Q6AEwAXoECAAQAg|title=History of Karachi: With Special Reference to Educational, Demographical, and Commercial Developments, 1839-1900|date=1974|publisher=Haider|language=en}}</ref>\n\nKarachi's most elite Catholic institutions were quickly established in Karachi: St Patrick\u2019s High School and St Joseph\u2019s Convent High School, wereset up in 1861 and 1862 respectively.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://arifhasan.org/culture/karachi-ch/the-future-of-karachis-saddar|title=The Future Of Karachi\u2019s Saddar|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> The [[Edulji Dinshaw Dispensary]] was established in 1882. The \"McKenzie Pavilion Grounds\", now known as Jehangir Park, was established in 1883.<ref name=\":1\" /> [[Empress Market]] was established at the site of the execution grounds in 1889,<ref name=\":0\" /> and was originally meant to serve British administrators, soldiers, and their families. The area around the market saw the establishment of posh bars, cafes, and restaurants, such as the Saddar Tea Rooms, Elphinstone Restaurant, the old Todi shop and Caf\u00e9 Parisian.<ref name=\":1\" /> A dress-code was enforced in the posh Saddar area, leading it to be eventually known as the \"European Quarter\" of Karachi.<ref name=\":1\" />\nFollowing independence in 1947, Saddar remained a centre of multi-class interaction. Bars, clubs, and business catering to different social classes co-existed in the area.<ref name=\":1\" /> Several institutions of higher learning were within walking distance, including [[D. J. Sindh Government Science College]], and [[Sindh Muslim Law College]], and Regal Bazar became home to a weekly book market that still takes place.<ref name=\":1\" /> Saddar was also within easy walking distance from government institutions to the east of Saddar, and [[Civil Lines, Karachi|Civil Lines]] to the south. The most important churches in Karachi are located in Saddar, as well as Karachi's biggest Parsi fire temple. \n\nFollowing the abolishment of alcohol by [[Zulfikar Ali Bhutto]] in the early 1970s in an attempt to appease conservative forces, Saddar's nightlife scene was decimated.<ref name=\":1\" /> In 1977, dictator [[Muhammad Zia-ul-Haq]] instituted an Islamization agenda that was opposed by the city's wealthy and westernized elite. These classes withdrew from much of public life in Saddar, and instead established exclusive social clubs in Karachi's wealthy residential districts. As a result, Saddar's commercial markets began to serve only lower and lower-middle classes.<ref name=\":1\" /> The area remained a large commuter hub, and so hawker stalls began encroaching on sidewalks in order to cater to the growing number of commuters.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nA large multiplex cinema was established in the early 2000s, leading to a small wave of gentrification in the area. In 2019, in an effort to \"clean up\" the Empress Market, all stalls outside of the market which had been established in the plaza around the market were demolished in a controversial move.<ref name=\":1\" /> \n\n==Gallery ==\nThe following are heritage buildings in Saddar which are protected by the [[Government of Sindh]]:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://antiquities.sindhculture.gov.pk/index.php/publication/reports/111-karachi-heritage-building-re-survey-project/308-saddar-bazaar-quarter-february-2008|title=SADDAR BAZAAR QUARTER FEBRUARY 2008|website=antiquities.sindhculture.gov.pk|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref><gallery>\nFile:Mohammad Ali Building.jpg|The ''Mohamedali'' building is located on [[Zaibunnisa Street]].\nFile:Katchi Memon Masjid 02.jpg|The [[Kutchi Memon]] Mosque was built in Saddar, and is a major centre for Memons in the city.\nFile:St. Andrews church.jpg|[[St Andrew's Church, Karachi|St. Andrew's Church]] in Saddar was built in 1868.\nFile:Ilaco House Photo by Aliraza Khatri.jpg|Ilaco House on the corner of Dundass and [[Zaibunnisa Street|Zaibunnisa Streets]]\nFile:Khyber Hotel on a busy street.JPG|The colonial-era Khyber Hotel\nFile:Edulji Dinshaw Dispensary 01.jpg|[[Edulji Dinshaw Dispensary]], built in 1882\nFile:PK Karachi asv2020-02 img36 Empress Market.jpg|[[Empress Market]], built in 1889\