{"title_page": "Craig Mack", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Craig Mack\n| image              =\n| image_size         =\n| caption            =\n| birth_name         = Craig Jamieson Mack\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date|1970|05|10}}\n| birth_place        = [[The Bronx, New York City]], U.S.<ref>{{cite web|title=Craig Mack, \u2018Flava in Ya Ear\u2019 Rapper, Dead at 47|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/craig-mack-flava-in-ya-ear-rapper-dead-at-47-127656/|publisher=Rolling Stone|accessdate=28 May 2019}}</ref>\n| death_date         = {{Death date and age|2018|03|12|1970|05|10}}\n| death_place        = [[Walterboro, South Carolina]], U.S.<ref>{{cite web|title=Craig Mack Has Died Of Heart Failure At 47|url=https://www.xxlmag.com/news/2018/03/craig-mack-dead-46/|publisher=XXL Magazine|accessdate=28 May 2019}}</ref>\n| occupation         = Rapper\n| years_active       = {{hlist|1988\u20132006|2012\u20132018}}\n| children           = 2\n| website            = \n| module             = {{Infobox musical artist\n| embed = yes\n| background = solo_singer\n| genre = {{flatlist|\n* [[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]\n* [[Hardcore hip hop]]\n* [[East Coast hip hop]]\n}}\n| label = {{flatlist|\n* Mack World\n* [[Bad Boy Records|Bad Boy]]\n* [[Scotti Brothers Records|Scotti Brothers]]\n* Street Life\n* Def Squad\n* [[Arista Records|Arista]]\n}}\n| associated_acts = {{flatlist|\n* [[Sean Combs]]\n* [[The Notorious B.I.G.]]\n* [[Easy Mo Bee]]\n* [[DJ Scratch]]\n* [[EPMD]]\n}}\n  }}<!--end-module-->\n}}\n\n'''Craig Jamieson Mack''' (May 10, 1970{{cn|date=December 2019}} \u2013 March 12, 2018) was an American rapper and record producer. He helped build the foundation for [[Bad Boy Records]], one of hip hop\u2019s most influential labels. \n\nHe began rapping as a teenager under the name MC EZ and released one single in 1988, \"Just Rhymin'\" backed with \u201cGet Retarded,\u201d as part of MC EZ & Troup. Mack then became friends with the hip hop duo [[EPMD]] and eventually went on tour with them, doing jobs as a roadie. He helped [[DJ Scratch]] assemble and disassemble his turntables at shows. After a few years without forward movement in his recording career, Mack took advantage of an opportunity to rap for [[Sean Combs]], and secured a record deal with Combs\u2019s label, [[Bad Boy Records|Bad Boy]]. Mack is best known for his 1994 hit, \"[[Flava in Ya Ear]]\".\n\n==Career==\nHis first [[Single (music)|single]] \"Get Retarded/Just Rhymin'\" was released under the name MC EZ in 1988 on [[Fresh Records (US)|Fresh Records]].{{citation needed}} Mack is best known for his 1994 hit single \"[[Flava In Ya Ear]]\", which was released under his real name. The [[remix]] of the single was the breakout appearance of [[The Notorious B.I.G.]], as well as one of the first solo appearances by [[Busta Rhymes]].{{citation needed}} The success of The Notorious B.I.G.'s debut album, ''[[Ready to Die]]'', overshadowed Mack's early success on the Bad Boy label.\n\nAlthough Sean Combs mentioned in a 1994 interview on [[MTV]]'s ''[[Yo! MTV Raps]]'' that he was working with Mack on his second album, which was to be released sometime in January the following year, this proved to not be the case. Present at that interview (which also included The Notorious B.I.G.), Mack himself appeared puzzled by the statement.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZH7iA5HDWdM |title=Diddy/Puff Daddy CAUGHT Lying to Craig Mack about 2nd album!!! |publisher=YouTube |date= |accessdate=2012-04-09}}</ref> Mack did release a second album in 1997, but none of the singles charted and Mack was unable to repeat his success.{[citation needed}} In an interview, The Notorious B.I.G. says he appeared on the remix of \"Flava In Ya Ear\" for political reasons for Combs.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LVv4zGLTsek&t=113|title=Notorious BIG With Lil Cease Interview (Throwback Footage) |publisher=YouTube}}</ref> In 2002, Mack would appear in the music video for Puffy's single \"[[I Need a Girl (Part One)]]\".{{citation needed}}\n\nAfter a few attempts to return to success in the early-2000s, it was said that Mack was working on his third studio album in 2002, which was set to be released in 2007.{{citation needed}} The single \"Mack Tonight\" was released for the album in 2006.{{citation needed}} Mack then disappeared from the hip hop industry until in 2012, when a video was leaked on YouTube saying he had joined a Christian ministry, surprising family members and fans.{{citation needed}} From 2012 until his death, Mack resided in the [[Overcomer Ministry]] located in [[Walterboro, South Carolina]].<ref>Nicola Menzie, [http://www.christianpost.com/news/rapper-craig-mack-now-a-christian-testifies-of-leaving-wickedness-for-righteousness-in-church-video-101830/ \"Rapper Craig Mack, Now a Christian, Testifies of Leaving 'Wickedness' for 'Righteousness' in Church Video,\"] ''[[The Christian Post]]'', August 8, 2013.</ref> The Overcomer Ministry's YouTube channel released a video titled \"Craig Mack Testimony\" on May 22, 2016,<ref>{{Citation|last=The Overcomer Ministry|title=Craig Mack Testimony|date=2016-05-22|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MO5d6iNI_Ck|accessdate=2016-06-10}}</ref> in which Mack appears in the middle of the church to rap about Christianity through a remix of \"When God Comes\".<ref>{{Citation|last=BoomBap4Life|title=10 \u2013 When God Comes \u2013 Craig Mack|date=2011-04-10|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Us0nTZXee80|accessdate=2016-06-10}}</ref> The last part of the video entails a full version of the song with better production quality and a beat. The song expresses his personal beliefs. Mack planned to stay in the ministry and said that he had no intentions to come back to mainstream rap.{{citation needed}} The song also mentions that he \"moved [his] family to [[South Carolina]]\", which did not align with other reports expressing the family's concerns for his choices.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mediatakeout.com/mto-world-exclusive-former-bad-boy-artist-craig-mack-joins-a-cult-hes-living-in-a-compound-run-by-a-man-who-calls-himself-the-messiah/|title=MTO WORLD EXCLUSIVE!!! Former Bad Boy Artist Craig Mack JOINS A CULT!! (He's Living In A COMPOUND . . . Run By A Man Who Calls Himself THE MESSIAH) \u2013 MediaTakeOut.com\u2122|date=2012-03-08|website=MediaTakeOut.com\u2122|language=en-US|access-date=2016-06-10}}{{Dead link|date=July 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> According to the video, Mack felt he was doing \"wickedness\" in New York, and \"righteousness\" in South Carolina.<ref>{{Citation|last=tlink79|title=Craig Mack and His NEW RAP \u2013 The Video \u2013 See it LIVE!|date=2012-05-22|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dR1IEw-a7Qw|accessdate=2016-06-10}}</ref>\n\nOn November 26, 2012, Beazylife Distribution released a new Craig Mack mixtape, ''Operation Why2K? \u2013 Hosted by B-Eazy'', through DatPiff.com.{{citation needed}} In 2017, ''The Mack World Sessions'' was released, containing 18 tracks recorded between 2000 and 2006.{{citation needed}} Dutch record label, MECSMI, released the 'That's My Word' mixtape, hosted by DJ Tape Deck King, via DatPiff and YouTube on August 20, 2018.{{citation needed}} On November 25, 2018, 'That's My Word' posthumously won Mixtape of the Year at Bout Dat Online's Audio Dope Awards.{{citation needed}} This marked the first time Mack had won an award since \"Flava In Ya Ear\" won Single of the Year at the 1995 [[Source Awards]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://boutdatonline.com/2018/11/25/bout-dat-onlines-audio-dope-awards-2018-hosted-by-united-elementz-media-winners/|title=Bout Dat Online\u2019s Audio Dope Awards 2018 (hosted by United Elementz Media) \u2013 WINNERS!|date=2018-11-25|website=Bout Dat Online|language=en-US|access-date=2019-01-20}}</ref>\n\n==Death==\nMack died on March 12, 2018 from [[heart failure]] at a hospital near his home at [[Walterboro, South Carolina]].<ref>{{cite web|title=90s Hip hop star Craig Mack dead at 46|url=https://www.chron.com/entertainment/celebrities/article/90s-Hip-hop-star-Craig-Mack-dead-at-46-12748482.php|website=Houston Chronicle|accessdate=13 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Craig Mack, New York rapper on Diddy's Bad Boy label, dead at 46|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/craig-mack-new-york-rapper-diddy-bad-boy-label-dead-46-article-1.3871459|publisher=NY Daily News|accessdate=13 March 2018}}</ref> According to [[DJ Scratch]], he was ill for some time before his passing and was prepared for a grim outcome. Mack was apparently suffering from heart failure, having developed shortness of breath from around six months before his death when, according to rapper [[Erick Sermon]], he called his friends to bid farewell.<ref>{{cite web|title=Craig Mack Died of Congestive Heart Failure, Says Erick Sermon|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=WL6shIbh_EY|publisher=TMZ|accessdate=13 March 2018}}</ref> Following Mack's death, Sermon wrote on Twitter that he was finishing work on Craig Mack's new album. Mack is survived by his wife and two adult children.<ref>{{cite web|title=Craig Mack Dead at 47|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2018/03/craig-mack-dead|publisher=Complex|accessdate=28 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n\n===Studio albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:14em;\"| Title\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:18em;\"| Details\n! colspan=\"2\"| Peak chart positions\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:10em;\"| [[Music recording sales certification|Certifications]]<br><small>([[List of best selling music artists|sales threshold]])</small>\n|- style=\"font-size:smaller;\"\n! style=\"width:40px;\"| [[Billboard 200|US]]<br><ref>{{cite web|url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=craig mack|chart=Billboard 200}}|title=Craig Mack Album & Song Chart History \u2013 Billboard 200|work=Billboard|accessdate=May 27, 2011}}</ref>\n! style=\"width:40px;\"| [[Top R&B/Hip-Hop Albums|US R&B]]<br><ref>{{cite web|url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=craig mack|chart=R&B/Hip-Hop Albums B}}|title=Craig Mack Album & Song Chart History \u2013 R&B/Hip-Hop Albums|work=Billboard|accessdate=May 27, 2011}}.He know resides in Baldwin Hills, Ca</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Project Funk da World|Project: Funk da World]]\n| \n* Release date: September 20, 1994\n* Label: [[Bad Boy Records]]\n* Formats: [[Compact disc|CD]], [[Compact cassette|cassette]]\n| 21\n| 6\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| \n* [[Recording Industry Association of America|RIAA]]: Gold<ref name=\"RIAA\">{{cite web|url=http://riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?content_selector=gold-platinum-searchable-database |title=Recording Industry Association of America |publisher=RIAA |date= |accessdate=2012-04-09}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Operation: Get Down]]''\n| \n* Release date: June 24, 1997\n* Label: Street Life Records/[[Scotti Brothers Records|Scotti Brothers]]\n* Formats: CD, cassette\n| 46\n| 17\n| \n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''The Mack World Sessions''\n| \n* Release date: September 1, 2017\n* Label: Mack World\n* Formats: Digital download\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n!\n|}\n\n===Singles===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Years\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:14em;\"| Single\n! colspan=\"4\"| Peak chart positions\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:10.5em;\"| [[Music recording sales certification|Certifications]]<br><small>([[List of best selling music artists|sales threshold]])</small>\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Album\n|- style=\"font-size:smaller;\"\n! style=\"width:35px;\"| [[Billboard Hot 100|US]]<br><ref>{{cite web|url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=craig mack|chart=all}}|title=Craig Mack Album & Song Chart History \u2013 Hot 100|work=Billboard|accessdate=May 27, 2011}}</ref>\n! style=\"width:35px;\"| [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs|US R&B]]<br><ref>{{cite web|url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=craig mack|chart=R&B/Hip-Hop Songs}}|title=Craig Mack Album & Song Chart History \u2013 R&B/Hip-Hop Songs|work=Billboard|accessdate=May 27, 2011}}</ref>\n! style=\"width:35px;\"| [[Hot Rap Songs|US Rap]]<br><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/craig-mack-p44938/charts-awards/billboard-singles|title=Craig Mack : Allmusic : Billboard Singles|publisher=Allmusic|accessdate=May 27, 2011}}</ref>\n! style=\"width:35px;\"| [[UK Singles Chart|UK]]<br><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.zobbel.de/cluk/CLUK_M.HTM|title=Chart Log UK: M \u2013 My Vitriol|publisher=[[The Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=May 27, 2011}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 1994\n! scope=\"row\"| \"[[Flava in Ya Ear]]\"\n| 9\n| 4\n| 1\n| 57\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| \n* RIAA: Platinum<ref name=\"RIAA\"/>\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" rowspan=\"2\"| ''Project: Funk Da World''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"[[Get Down (Craig Mack song)|Get Down]]\"\n| 38\n| 17\n| 2\n| 54\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| \n* RIAA: Gold<ref name=\"RIAA\"/>\n|-\n| 1997\n! scope=\"row\"| \"What I Need\"\n| 103\n| 55\n| 16\n| \u2014\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| \n| style=\"text-align:left;\" rowspan=\"2\"| ''Operation: Get Down''\n|-\n| 1998\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Jockin My Style\"\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| Jockin My Style=\"text-align:left;\"| \n|-\n| 1999 \n! scope=\"row\" | \"Wooden Horse\"<br /><small>(featuring [[Frank Sinatra]])</small> \n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014 \n| \n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| ''[[What's the Worst That Could Happen? (soundtrack)|What's the Worst That Could Happen?]]'' & The Mack World Sessions\n|-\n| colspan=\"10\" style=\"font-size:8pt\"| \"\u2014\" denotes releases that did not chart\n|}\n\n===Music videos===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Video\n! Director\n|-\n| 1994\n| \"Flava in Ya Ear\"\n| Craig Henry\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mack, Craig}}\n[[Category:African-American Christians]]\n[[Category:African-American male rappers]]\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:2018 deaths]]\n[[Category:Rappers from the Bronx]]\n[[Category:East Coast hip hop musicians]]\n[[Category:Bad Boy Records artists]]\n[[Category:Brentwood High School (Brentwood, New York) alumni]]\n[[Category:African-American songwriters]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:American hip hop record producers]]\n[[Category:African-American record producers]]\n[[Category:People from Brentwood, New York]]\n[[Category:People from Walterboro, South Carolina]]\n[[Category:Record producers from New York (state)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Craig Mack\n| image              =\n| image_size         =\n| caption            =\n| birth_name         = Craig Jamieson Mack\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date|1970|05|10}}\n| birth_place        = [[The Bronx, New York City]], U.S.<ref>{{cite web|title=Craig Mack, \u2018Flava in Ya Ear\u2019 Rapper, Dead at 47|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/craig-mack-flava-in-ya-ear-rapper-dead-at-47-127656/|publisher=Rolling Stone|accessdate=28 May 2019}}</ref>\n| death_date         = {{Death date and age|2018|03|12|1970|05|10}}\n| death_place        = [[Walterboro, South Carolina]], U.S.<ref>{{cite web|title=Craig Mack Has Died Of Heart Failure At 47|url=https://www.xxlmag.com/news/2018/03/craig-mack-dead-46/|publisher=XXL Magazine|accessdate=28 May 2019}}</ref>\n| occupation         = Rapper\n| years_active       = {{hlist|1988\u20132006|2012\u20132018}}\n| children           = 2\n| website            = \n| module             = {{Infobox musical artist\n| embed = yes\n| background = solo_singer\n| genre = {{flatlist|\n* [[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]\n* [[Hardcore hip hop]]\n* [[East Coast hip hop]]\n}}\n| label = {{flatlist|\n* Mack World\n* [[Bad Boy Records|Bad Boy]]\n* [[Scotti Brothers Records|Scotti Brothers]]\n* Street Life\n* Def Squad\n* [[Arista Records|Arista]]\n}}\n| associated_acts = {{flatlist|\n* [[Sean Combs]]\n* [[The Notorious B.I.G.]]\n* [[Easy Mo Bee]]\n* [[DJ Scratch]]\n* [[EPMD]]\n}}\n  }}<!--end-module-->\n}}\n\n'''Craig Jamieson Mack''' (May 10, 1970{{cn|date=December 2019}} \u2013 March 12, 2018) was an American rapper and record producer. He helped build the foundation for [[Bad Boy Records]], one of hip hop\u2019s most influential labels. \n\nHe began rapping as a teenager under the name MC EZ and released one single in 1988, \"Just Rhymin'\" backed with \u201cGet Retarded,\u201d as part of MC EZ & Troup. Mack then became friends with the hip hop duo [[EPMD]] and eventually went on tour with them, doing jobs as a roadie. He helped [[DJ Scratch]] assemble and disassemble his turntables at shows. After a few years without forward movement in his recording career, Mack took advantage of an opportunity to rap for [[Sean Combs]], and secured a record deal with Combs\u2019s label, [[Bad Boy Records|Bad Boy]]. Mack is best known for his 1994 hit, \"[[Flava in Ya Ear]]\".\n\n==Career==\nHis first [[Single (music)|single]] \"Get Retarded/Just Rhymin'\" was released under the name MC EZ in 1988 on [[Fresh Records (US)|Fresh Records]].{{citation needed}} Mack is best known for his 1994 hit single \"[[Flava In Ya Ear]]\", which was released under his real name. The [[remix]] of the single was the breakout appearance of [[The Notorious B.I.G.]], as well as one of the first solo appearances by [[Busta Rhymes]].{{citation needed}} The success of The Notorious B.I.G.'s debut album, ''[[Ready to Die]]'', overshadowed Mack's early success on the Bad Boy label.\n\nAlthough Sean Combs mentioned in a 1994 interview on [[MTV]]'s ''[[Yo! MTV Raps]]'' that he was working with Mack on his second album, which was to be released sometime in January the following year, this proved to not be the case. Present at that interview (which also included The Notorious B.I.G.), Mack himself appeared puzzled by the statement.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZH7iA5HDWdM |title=Diddy/Puff Daddy CAUGHT Lying to Craig Mack about 2nd album!!! |publisher=YouTube |date= |accessdate=2012-04-09}}</ref> Mack did release a second album in 1997, but none of the singles charted and Mack was unable to repeat his success.{[citation needed}} In an interview, The Notorious B.I.G. says he appeared on the remix of \"Flava In Ya Ear\" for political reasons for Combs.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LVv4zGLTsek&t=113|title=Notorious BIG With Lil Cease Interview (Throwback Footage) |publisher=YouTube}}</ref> In 2002, Mack would appear in the music video for Puffy's single \"[[I Need a Girl (Part One)]]\".{{citation needed}}\n\nAfter a few attempts to return to success in the early-2000s, it was said that Mack was working on his third studio album in 2002, which was set to be released in 2007.{{citation needed}} The single \"Mack Tonight\" was released for the album in 2006.{{citation needed}} Mack then disappeared from the hip hop industry until in 2012, when a video was leaked on YouTube saying he had joined a Christian ministry, surprising family members and fans.{{citation needed}} From 2012 until his death, Mack resided in the [[Overcomer Ministry]] located in [[Walterboro, South Carolina]].<ref>Nicola Menzie, [http://www.christianpost.com/news/rapper-craig-mack-now-a-christian-testifies-of-leaving-wickedness-for-righteousness-in-church-video-101830/ \"Rapper Craig Mack, Now a Christian, Testifies of Leaving 'Wickedness' for 'Righteousness' in Church Video,\"] ''[[The Christian Post]]'', August 8, 2013.</ref> The Overcomer Ministry's YouTube channel released a video titled \"Craig Mack Testimony\" on May 22, 2016,<ref>{{Citation|last=The Overcomer Ministry|title=Craig Mack Testimony|date=2016-05-22|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MO5d6iNI_Ck|accessdate=2016-06-10}}</ref> in which Mack appears in the middle of the church to rap about Christianity through a remix of \"When God Comes\".<ref>{{Citation|last=BoomBap4Life|title=10 \u2013 When God Comes \u2013 Craig Mack|date=2011-04-10|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Us0nTZXee80|accessdate=2016-06-10}}</ref> The last part of the video entails a full version of the song with better production quality and a beat. The song expresses his personal beliefs. Mack planned to stay in the ministry and said that he had no intentions to come back to mainstream rap.{{citation needed}} The song also mentions that he \"moved [his] family to [[South Carolina]]\", which did not align with other reports expressing the family's concerns for his choices.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mediatakeout.com/mto-world-exclusive-former-bad-boy-artist-craig-mack-joins-a-cult-hes-living-in-a-compound-run-by-a-man-who-calls-himself-the-messiah/|title=MTO WORLD EXCLUSIVE!!! Former Bad Boy Artist Craig Mack JOINS A CULT!! (He's Living In A COMPOUND . . . Run By A Man Who Calls Himself THE MESSIAH) \u2013 MediaTakeOut.com\u2122|date=2012-03-08|website=MediaTakeOut.com\u2122|language=en-US|access-date=2016-06-10}}{{Dead link|date=July 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> According to the video, Mack felt he was doing \"wickedness\" in New York, and \"righteousness\" in South Carolina.<ref>{{Citation|last=tlink79|title=Craig Mack and His NEW RAP \u2013 The Video \u2013 See it LIVE!|date=2012-05-22|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dR1IEw-a7Qw|accessdate=2016-06-10}}</ref>\n\nOn November 26, 2012, Beazylife Distribution released a new Craig Mack mixtape, ''Operation Why2K? \u2013 Hosted by B-Eazy'', through DatPiff.com.{{citation needed}} In 2017, ''The Mack World Sessions'' was released, containing 18 tracks recorded between 2000 and 2006.{{citation needed}} Dutch record label, MECSMI, released the 'That's My Word' mixtape, hosted by DJ Tape Deck King, via DatPiff and YouTube on August 20, 2018.{{citation needed}} On November 25, 2018, 'That's My Word' posthumously won Mixtape of the Year at Bout Dat Online's Audio Dope Awards.{{citation needed}} This marked the first time Mack had won an award since \"Flava In Ya Ear\" won Single of the Year at the 1995 [[Source Awards]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://boutdatonline.com/2018/11/25/bout-dat-onlines-audio-dope-awards-2018-hosted-by-united-elementz-media-winners/|title=Bout Dat Online\u2019s Audio Dope Awards 2018 (hosted by United Elementz Media) \u2013 WINNERS!|date=2018-11-25|website=Bout Dat Online|language=en-US|access-date=2019-01-20}}</ref>\n\n==Death==\nMack died on March 12, 2018 from [[heart failure]] at a hospital near his home at [[Walterboro, South Carolina]].<ref>{{cite web|title=90s Hip hop star Craig Mack dead at 46|url=https://www.chron.com/entertainment/celebrities/article/90s-Hip-hop-star-Craig-Mack-dead-at-46-12748482.php|website=Houston Chronicle|accessdate=13 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Craig Mack, New York rapper on Diddy's Bad Boy label, dead at 46|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/craig-mack-new-york-rapper-diddy-bad-boy-label-dead-46-article-1.3871459|publisher=NY Daily News|accessdate=13 March 2018}}</ref> According to [[DJ Scratch]] he was ill for some time before his passing and was prepared for a grim outcome. Mack was apparently suffering from heart failure, having developed shortness of breath from around six months before his death when, according to rapper [[Erick Sermon]], he called his friends to bid farewell.<ref>{{cite web|title=Craig Mack Died of Congestive Heart Failure, Says Erick Sermon|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=WL6shIbh_EY|publisher=TMZ|accessdate=13 March 2018}}</ref> Following Mack's death, Sermon wrote on Twitter that he was finishing work on Craig Mack's new album. Mack is survived by his wife and two adult children.<ref>{{cite web|title=Craig Mack Dead at 47|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2018/03/craig-mack-dead|publisher=Complex|accessdate=28 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n\n===Studio albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"